Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.51,0:01:01.85,Default,,0,0,0,,you see Hobbes, you see all the great names of history, and then you see\NImmanuel Kant who set up the categories, the categories of abstraction, and all
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.85,0:01:12.13,Default,,0,0,0,,the time on television you hear people violate the various levels, they violate\Nthe various levels. Here's the great names, Sir Isaac Newton, so there's three
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.13,0:01:28.33,Default,,0,0,0,,interesting geniuses, Sigmund Freud calibrates at 499, Sir Isaac Newton\Ncalibrates at 499, who is Z equals something, C squared? Einstein at 499, all
Dialogue: 0,0:01:28.33,0:01:43.80,Default,,0,0,0,,of them. See because at 500 there's a new paradigm. You move from that which is\Nsupposedly objective logical sequential to the subjective, which is not provable.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.80,0:01:53.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Advanced spiritual truth then is not provable because it's a\Ndifferent paradigm. That which is provable is not spiritual truth,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.39,0:02:05.27,Default,,0,0,0,,because you are always in competition.\NBecause you would be stating something within the limitation of the dualistic Newtonian paradigm, which is linear.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.56,0:02:27.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Spiritual reality is non-linear, not provable, not demonstrable, subjectively experiential, and hugely transformative.\NEven one or two mild spiritual experiences, whoa, not to mention a near-death experience or something transformative like that.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.90,0:02:31.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Which totally changes you forever.\NNear-death experience.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.40,0:02:42.73,Default,,0,0,0,,This is as far as the human psyche goes.\NSophocles, the great names of history.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:43.01,0:02:49.42,Default,,0,0,0,,The great names of history.\NAnd when I was a kid, Socrates was my hero.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.56,0:02:59.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Socrates, of course, didn't write anything.\NBut, of course, his teachings are well described in Plato, etc.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.85,0:03:07.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Socrates calibrates at 512.\NHe was, to me, a great spiritual teacher, one of my heroes.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.78,0:03:17.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Socrates, actually, was willing to die for truth.\NNow, in the days of Socrates, there wasn't the Catholic Church.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:17.34,0:03:22.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Buddhism was on the other side of the world.\NHindu sages were on the other side of the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.86,0:03:40.26,Default,,0,0,0,,And, therefore, in a really, in a way, non-religious society, Socrates intuited truth at the level of 540, unconditional love.\NAnd Socrates, when he was accused of perverting the minds of youth by teaching them the kind of things I'm teaching today.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.46,0:03:52.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Where's my hemlock, by the way?\NEither had to change what he was teaching or drink the hemlock.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.79,0:04:06.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Socrates chose hemlock rather than violate the truth.\NSocrates chose death rather than physical life because of his alignment with truth.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.09,0:04:13.97,Default,,0,0,0,,One of Socrates' best sayings is a very useful one.\NAnd, pragmatically, for all of us on an almost daily basis.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.04,0:04:23.44,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, even now, with the coming elections, it's very good to know.\NSocrates said something that really resolves just about everything.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.43,0:04:29.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Man only chooses the good.\NMan always chooses the good.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.89,0:04:36.92,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, he can only choose that which he envisions as good.\NThe only trouble is he doesn't know which is the good.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.36,0:04:48.08,Default,,0,0,0,,And he chooses the temporary and illusory rather than the infinite and perpetual.\NOn the other hand, his intention is always to choose what he feels to be the good.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.33,0:04:54.68,Default,,0,0,0,,What he thinks to be the good.\NUnfortunately, it might be killing you.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.16,0:05:07.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Blowing up a busload of children.\NBut, he believes that it is for the good.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.97,0:05:17.31,Default,,0,0,0,,So that sort of seconds man's intrinsic innocence because the Buddha, Krishna, and Christ,\Nevery great being that ever lived, said man only has one defect.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.55,0:05:21.31,Default,,0,0,0,,And that's ignorance.\NHe doesn't know the good from the bad.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.31,0:05:24.05,Default,,0,0,0,,He doesn't know.\NHe thinks that it's good.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:24.33,0:05:31.55,Default,,0,0,0,,So he votes for illusion.\NHe sacrifices his life for illusion because he cannot tell truth from falsehood.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.48,0:05:41.36,Default,,0,0,0,,You see the incredible gift that we have right now?\NFor the first time in the evolution of all of time, we can tell truth from falsehood.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.24,0:05:48.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Not only that, but within an instant.\NWow. Think of the positive karma of a group like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.83,0:05:58.40,Default,,0,0,0,,People on the earth today now, for the first time, can tell truth from falsehood.\NMan only chooses the good.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.58,0:06:07.52,Default,,0,0,0,,So those of us who look favorably on the Course in Miracles,\Nyou know, the Course in Miracles is based on forgiveness.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:08.40,0:06:14.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, how can you forgive people if they're wrong?\NThat's the question that always arises.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.57,0:06:21.52,Default,,0,0,0,,And if they're bad and evil, how can you forgive people if they're wrong, bad, and evil?\NIt's because...
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.76,0:06:35.42,Default,,0,0,0,,They saw that, was that killing you was to their highest good.\NThe fact that they get to go to heaven, and 3,000 kids get to be blown up in a bus is the price of it,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.84,0:06:42.36,Default,,0,0,0,,would seem to us an illusion.\NBut perhaps to their extreme viewpoint, that is truth.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.02,0:06:53.50,Default,,0,0,0,,So therefore, we can see the innate innocence.\NBecause each of us, then, is born with hardware, the hardware,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.36,0:06:56.90,Default,,0,0,0,,and then superimposed...\NSuperimposed on that is software.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.78,0:07:03.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, the hardware cannot protect itself against the software.\NThe human mind is like the hardware.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.96,0:07:08.59,Default,,0,0,0,,And now it gets programmed with software.\NIt doesn't have any switch.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.65,0:07:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,That when you try to put falsity into it, it goes...\NDoesn't do that.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.58,0:07:24.12,Default,,0,0,0,,That's the tragedy.\NSo we can see that instead of evil and hatred,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.46,0:07:33.37,Default,,0,0,0,,perhaps compassion for the tragedy of ignorance,\Nthe tragedy of ignorance costs the lives of 10 million, 10 million.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.07,0:07:46.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, the calibrated levels of the great books of the Western world calibrate around 450 or something.\NBut if you remove this guy here, Karl Marx, the whole collective total comes out at 460.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:47.60,0:07:56.98,Default,,0,0,0,,So the difficulty with the recent world and today's social world is the perpetrator-victim model,\Nthe dualistic creation.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.98,0:07:59.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Marx had an unresolved...\Nmethod of a complex.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.02,0:08:08.02,Default,,0,0,0,,And he revolted against the leading philosopher of his day, Hegel.\NWhen Hegel's basic teachings was that of the absolute,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.05,0:08:18.71,Default,,0,0,0,,what you saw that he demonstrated is the influence of the absolute.\NThe infinite field of consciousness, which is what we consult with kinesiology all the time,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:18.97,0:08:22.55,Default,,0,0,0,,is the absolute field.\NHegel said,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.55,0:08:30.58,Default,,0,0,0,,all are accountable because of the principle of the absolute.\NWell, if there's anything that Eagleton...
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.58,0:08:47.14,Default,,0,0,0,,ego hates is to hear that it's not God. The ego secretly thinks it is God, and it hates God and\Ndisguises that hatred in many forms. At least the secularists are honest. They hate God, and the word
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.14,0:08:57.03,Default,,0,0,0,,makes them very nervous and upset, so they want to remove it. At least they're honest about it, you\Nsee. The ego is more clever than that. It gets rid of God by getting rid of the sovereignty of the
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.03,0:09:14.91,Default,,0,0,0,,absolute, the sovereignty of the absolute. It's the sovereignty of the absolute that the core of the\Nnarcissistic ego hates, and the ego hates God. So, Marx had an unresolved, edible complex. I speak as a,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.17,0:09:26.30,Default,,0,0,0,,you know, I did 50 years of psychoanalysis and psychiatry, was psychoanalyzed by myself, one of the\Nworld's most famous and best. Deep within the unconscious, there is a hatred of that which
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.30,0:09:35.11,Default,,0,0,0,,represents authority, the father figure.\NIf your experience with your father was benign, you see authority as friendly and protective. If your
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.11,0:09:48.20,Default,,0,0,0,,experience or your image, not necessarily your reality experience, at least your image of your father, was\Nthreatening, then you confuse authority with authoritarianism, and you hate all authority because you think
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.20,0:10:01.31,Default,,0,0,0,,it's authoritarian, and you fail to see the legitimacy of true authority. For one thing, information, fact, and\Nknowledge is itself an authority.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.09,0:10:21.83,Default,,0,0,0,,So, the current relativistic philosophers even hate science and logic, you know, the problematic hermeneutics of relativistic epistemology.\NYou first heard it here.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.29,0:10:38.92,Default,,0,0,0,,The probabilistic hermeneutics of relativistic epistemology is why the classroom of America, which used to calibrate in the\N1800s, it now calibrates to about 190.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.92,0:11:02.10,Default,,0,0,0,,The denigration of logic, reason, the discipline that goes with that.\NYeah, so, anyway, because of Marx's unresolved Oedipal Complex, he, which I say is a fact, resist, he was his Oedipal Complex,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:02.10,0:11:09.74,Default,,0,0,0,,resist. Okay, just check my psychoanalysts, see if he's right. I sweated it out on couch, so I mean I'm screaming.\NOkay, just check my psychoanalysts, see if he's right. I sweated it out on couch, so I mean I'm screaming.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:09.86,0:11:17.94,Default,,0,0,0,,experientially. You know, 50 years of psychiatry, nobody ever came in\Nthat didn't have an Oedipal complex or so on. He would be from a different planet
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.94,0:11:26.06,Default,,0,0,0,,because you grow up with parents, so you're going to see one view as the maternal\Npermissive, all-inclusive, non-judgmental, and then you're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:11:26.06,0:11:33.90,Default,,0,0,0,,see the father figure that says, yes, that's nice, but\Nif you've got a job, you've got to go to work every day. You just can't call in and say, I don't feel like
Dialogue: 0,0:11:33.90,0:11:42.02,Default,,0,0,0,,going to work today. You won't have a job on Monday. The maternal\Nis permissive and inclusive, and the paternal stands
Dialogue: 0,0:11:42.02,0:11:50.52,Default,,0,0,0,,more for the survival in the external world.\NAnyway, Hegel was the authority father figure,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:51.59,0:11:59.47,Default,,0,0,0,,and its impact, this unresolved Oedipal complex here\Nhas impacted all of life in our current society.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:59.75,0:12:06.99,Default,,0,0,0,,That error, that error of failure\Nof truth, that fallacy, has cost tens of millions
Dialogue: 0,0:12:06.99,0:12:14.60,Default,,0,0,0,,of lives.\NMillions of lives have been slaughtered by the error of
Dialogue: 0,0:12:14.60,0:12:24.17,Default,,0,0,0,,projecting, rest in turn, seeing perpetrator and victim\Nout there in the world. There is no perpetrator and victim out there in the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:26.45,0:12:32.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Everything comes about as a consequence of the field,\Nplus your karma and your calibrated level of consciousness.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:34.26,0:12:41.72,Default,,0,0,0,,How can you turn everything into perpetrator and victim? You'll see that's today's\Nsocial contention, the whole litiginous, sociologic
Dialogue: 0,0:12:41.72,0:12:46.81,Default,,0,0,0,,disaster.\NA disaster sees everything as innocent victim and
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.81,0:12:54.87,Default,,0,0,0,,wicked perpetrator.\NNo such thing exists in the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:56.26,0:13:09.40,Default,,0,0,0,,That is a perception projected onto society.\NA company moves into town, theology of Wisconsin, and their
Dialogue: 0,0:13:09.40,0:13:14.55,Default,,0,0,0,,county company at heine's ball or other poor little farmer\Nneighborhood.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:14.55,0:13:22.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Now people, they're crops are bought instantly, whole crop.\NThe company makes money because they're maping their future to a new type of farming.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.04,0:13:30.49,Default,,0,0,0,,they've got inexpensive labor and they're right there in the middle of\Nwhere the growing fields are the town prospers people now can buy cars they
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.49,0:13:41.55,Default,,0,0,0,,can afford telephones and they put down electricity electricity down one side of\Nthe highway and company makes money and people invest in the company and the
Dialogue: 0,0:13:41.55,0:13:50.71,Default,,0,0,0,,consumer gets products on the field you don't have to can all your own peas so I\Nworked there and you got paid a nickel an hour for everything extra over 12
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.71,0:14:03.38,Default,,0,0,0,,hours 30 cents an hour and if you work more than 12 hours you got 35 cents\Neverybody was happy I was happy I had an income the town was happy the company
Dialogue: 0,0:14:03.38,0:14:15.64,Default,,0,0,0,,was happy then how do you find a perpetrator and victim in there you have\Nthat as a belief system now you walk into the town you say well look the
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.64,0:14:23.48,Default,,0,0,0,,company's exploiting the workers then you can walk the other way around say\Nthe workers are milking the company no no now the townspeople are willed
Dialogue: 0,0:14:23.48,0:14:33.17,Default,,0,0,0,,milking the employees oh no the employees are milking the townspeople no\Nthe shopkeepers are but this is all happening in your head I lived there I
Dialogue: 0,0:14:33.17,0:14:43.61,Default,,0,0,0,,experienced it I got the 30 to 35 cents I used to hope that it would last over\N12 hours guys because I got 35 cents you can call that oppressive if you want but
Dialogue: 0,0:14:43.61,0:14:53.27,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll tell you when you need money I was happy to have there's your five cents an\Nhour and as you can make $40 a month I mean you know riches Rockefeller yeah
Dialogue: 0,0:14:54.92,0:15:09.92,Default,,0,0,0,,therefore the error so to be able to use calibration techniques how can you\Ntell if a statement is truthful or not truthful yeah unless you can depend on a
Dialogue: 0,0:15:09.92,0:15:23.29,Default,,0,0,0,,reliable source of discerning truth and falsehood the kinesiologic method is the\Nfirst way 135 is way down from truth isn't it what truth is at 200 135 is
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.29,0:15:35.57,Default,,0,0,0,,way down now you've got huge countries\NChina Russia giant countries being run by a consciousness level belief system at
Dialogue: 0,0:15:35.57,0:15:55.74,Default,,0,0,0,,135 135 brings death destruction paranoia the KGB the secret police\Nsecret killings brings pull pot or pot pull whatever that is name is pull pot
Dialogue: 0,0:15:55.74,0:16:05.56,Default,,0,0,0,,pull went to pot potty pull I don't know what it is\NI mean yet you know we're not just speaking academically today talking
Dialogue: 0,0:16:05.56,0:16:17.76,Default,,0,0,0,,about the lives of tens of millions of people in my lifetime died for\Nfalsehood tens of millions tens of millions died for falsehood the
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.76,0:16:30.68,Default,,0,0,0,,inability to discern truth from falsehood hmm\Nall right so here's the content here's the proximate field years the internet
Dialogue: 0,0:16:30.68,0:16:38.72,Default,,0,0,0,,field so here's the Internet field of consciousness\Ninfinitely power. This is powerful. This is what we consult with kinesiology. This is the absolute
Dialogue: 0,0:16:38.72,0:16:55.43,Default,,0,0,0,,as compared to the absolute, which is infinite. This statement calibrates so far. So this is the\Nabsolute spoken of by Hegel and which would give Karl Marx nightmares if he was reborn today,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.43,0:17:14.34,Default,,0,0,0,,because I'd say this is the criteria of truth and not your narcissistic ego. This is the proximate\Nfield. The second naivete is any statement is only true within a stated context. The naivete of the
Dialogue: 0,0:17:14.34,0:17:26.38,Default,,0,0,0,,human mind, it thinks only in terms of limitation. This is not a great diagram, but we're going to\Nmake a better one. We were going to make a better diagram. Anyway, this is the linear definable
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.38,0:17:36.36,Default,,0,0,0,,world of Newtonian.\NIn science, you can measure it. This is the field of the scientific reductionist, the materialistic
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.36,0:17:52.71,Default,,0,0,0,,reductionist. Unless you can measure it, weigh it, score it, it's not real. This is the linear\Nstatement that so-and-so is true, that so-and-so lied, so-and-so didn't lie, et cetera, that a
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.71,0:18:07.99,Default,,0,0,0,,certain law violates human rights or something.\NThe statement is only true within a certain context. That's true under this context. It is not true
Dialogue: 0,0:18:07.99,0:18:23.54,Default,,0,0,0,,on another context. The rules that apply to the population in times of war are quite different than\Nthe ones that apply in times of peace. It's confused. So truth is only true if you state in what
Dialogue: 0,0:18:23.54,0:18:40.01,Default,,0,0,0,,context, in what context. So the context then is the proximate field. The proximate field is the\Nconditions, climate, population, wealth, a thousand things. A thing is only true under certain
Dialogue: 0,0:18:40.01,0:18:56.43,Default,,0,0,0,,conditions. The conditions which the naive mind thinks are causal, they're not causal. They're just\Nconditions. Rain and humidity and barometric pressure and altitude. If you try to find the
Dialogue: 0,0:18:56.43,0:19:11.02,Default,,0,0,0,,cause of anything within the Newtonian paradigm of cause and effect, you will find that every single\Nevent, supposed event, has an infinite number of causes, that the world of causality is an illusion.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.02,0:19:23.80,Default,,0,0,0,,If you say, what is the cause of this little speck of dust being here right now? Well, it depends on\Nthe barometric pressure, the ozone, depends on the altitude, depends on the wind speed, it depends on
Dialogue: 0,0:19:23.80,0:19:31.68,Default,,0,0,0,,what time of the year, it depends on temperature, barometric pressure. It would have to occur in a\Nbuilding, so somebody would have to create this building for this little piece of dust to be here,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.68,0:19:38.98,Default,,0,0,0,,and this building requires a state to be in.\NWhich requires a globe, which requires a universe. So you can see a complete explanation of why this
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.98,0:19:51.90,Default,,0,0,0,,little piece of dust is right here. The number of factors is infinite, infinite, infinite. And then\Nyou will realize that you're dealing in an illusion. There is no cause for it to be, because phenomena
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.90,0:20:03.98,Default,,0,0,0,,are like clouds appearing in the sky. The cloud appears as a consequence of the totality of the\Nenvironment, condensing and presenting itself thusly.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.30,0:20:21.30,Default,,0,0,0,,There's no cause for a cloud. No cause. No cause. It's not caused. It's the consequence of the field.\NWhen all factors are favorable, then it emerges spontaneously of its own. And when they're not, it fades away
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.30,0:20:36.34,Default,,0,0,0,,of its own. You say, well, the wind is causing it. The wind's not causing it, there's wind there all the time.\NAll right, so this is the infinite contact which we can solve, the absolute, when we consult with kinesiologists.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:36.34,0:20:51.88,Default,,0,0,0,,We say, as compared to the absolute, this calibrates as so much. Okay, we'll move on.\NThe content field and context, this is just in words. The content in the center is limited.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:51.88,0:21:07.97,Default,,0,0,0,,That's the ego, the linear, definable, measurable, and it deals in force.\NThe infinite field deals in power. Force moves from here to there. Consequently, force always creates
Dialogue: 0,0:21:07.97,0:21:16.93,Default,,0,0,0,,counter-force.\NAs Napoleon and everybody else has found out through history, forcing people to do things results in counter-force.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:16.93,0:21:30.93,Default,,0,0,0,,If it evolves as a consequence of the field, then it has no enemies, because now it's coming out of power.\NAnd power is aligned with truth. Therefore, that which is truthful, then, and integrous, eventually influences
Dialogue: 0,0:21:30.93,0:21:48.24,Default,,0,0,0,,what is witnessed within the world, but not in a cause and effect way. It may be delayed over time.\NWhy? Because truth then begins to set a context by which everything is measured. Everything is measured by.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:48.24,0:22:05.97,Default,,0,0,0,,And its effect may be slow. So, force is quick and temporary. Power is slow.\NSo, force is like hitting something, and power is like gravity. Gravity just stands there.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:05.97,0:22:15.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, force, you have to constantly feed it energy. It's always wearing out. You have to feed it.\NMilitary supplies, battle, money, tax money, etc.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:15.16,0:22:28.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Force then exhausts itself and creates counter-force.\NPower then just merely stands there, controls everything within it.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:28.65,0:22:39.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Every iron filing within the gravitational field is at the effect of the field.\NIt has no opposition. It has no opposite. So, truth has no opposite.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:39.74,0:22:48.02,Default,,0,0,0,,There is no opposite to truth. There is only its absence.\NTruth is either present or not present.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.02,0:23:00.22,Default,,0,0,0,,With the kinesiologic response, what you see is in the presence of truth,\Nthe energy flows down the acupuncture system. The body goes instantly strong in the presence of truth.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:00.22,0:23:14.73,Default,,0,0,0,,It's almost like protoplasm recognizes that which is supportive of life.\NAnd in the presence of falsehood, the arm goes weak because protoplasm, on an even physical level,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:14.73,0:23:23.73,Default,,0,0,0,,protoplasm knows what is inimicable to life.\NThe amoeba goes towards that which supports its survival. It withdraws.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:23.73,0:23:32.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Even protoplasm, which is an impersonal response.\NSo, the kinesiologic response is impersonal.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:32.87,0:23:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The proximate field is the spiritual ego. It's semi-linear.\NIt seems to be random.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.00,0:23:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It's definable not within the Newtonian, but more by non-linear dynamics.\NThe field tends to quickly do a thing like, see what it did again?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:50.00,0:23:57.10,Default,,0,0,0,,If you don't watch it, it'll just fly out by itself.\NYou have to tuck it in someplace, make it stop.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:57.10,0:24:09.02,Default,,0,0,0,,It's unpredictable.\NExtreme sports. I always say something about extreme sports.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.02,0:24:14.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Not trying to keep them alive past their time to leave this world.\NNever.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:14.40,0:24:24.70,Default,,0,0,0,,But so you understand non-linear dynamics,\Nthat after 32 jumps from the plane,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:24.70,0:24:29.70,Default,,0,0,0,,number 33 is coming up.\NAnd that's the non-linear dynamics.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:29.70,0:24:39.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Out of regularity, unpredictably comes non-regularity.\NRemember that computer chip had an error in the 26th decimal point?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:39.86,0:24:45.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Somebody in the audience always remembers the name of that chip.\NRemember that? It was about 25 years ago?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:45.46,0:24:53.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Huh? Intel?\NOkay. There was an error in the 26th decimal point.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:53.87,0:24:57.87,Default,,0,0,0,,And people said,\Nhow often is the 26th decimal point going to come up?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:57.87,0:25:01.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Forget it.\NExcept that by iteration, meaning repetition,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:01.90,0:25:08.90,Default,,0,0,0,,millions and millions of times,\N26th decimal point can only change the whole course of civilization.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:08.90,0:25:12.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Whoa.\NSo, all right.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:12.06,0:25:16.86,Default,,0,0,0,,So non-linear dynamics.\NI always bring that up.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:16.86,0:25:21.86,Default,,0,0,0,,And the infinite context we call spirit.\NNow, linear, unlimited.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:21.86,0:25:24.86,Default,,0,0,0,,It's purely experiential.\NYou cannot prove it.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:24.86,0:25:29.82,Default,,0,0,0,,It's self-existent.\NIt's subjective.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:29.82,0:25:31.82,Default,,0,0,0,,It's knowable.\NIt's experiential.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:31.82,0:25:34.82,Default,,0,0,0,,It's non-local.\NOkay, we'll go to the next.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:34.82,0:25:42.86,Default,,0,0,0,,So just so we define the different context.\NThe spiritual foundation is a novelty in today's world.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:42.86,0:25:49.94,Default,,0,0,0,,But in the world I grew up, it's the way the world was.\NIn Wisconsin, this is the way everybody was.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:49.94,0:25:56.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Chicago, by the way, calibrates at 440.\NSo if you have an adolescent child who's lost himself,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:56.20,0:26:01.20,Default,,0,0,0,,and has to go someplace on the planet to find himself,\NI'd suggest he go to Chicago.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:04.86,0:26:12.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Rather than Afghanistan or some place.\NThese are the virtues.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:12.46,0:26:18.46,Default,,0,0,0,,We're going to see how important they are.\NThey sound like, so what homilies, homilies.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:18.46,0:26:22.46,Default,,0,0,0,,No, in the world I grew up, everybody was this way.\NEverybody went to Boy Scouts.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:22.46,0:26:24.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Everybody went to church.\NEverybody was the Girl Scout.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:24.46,0:26:28.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Everybody belonged to the 4-H club.\NEverybody was honest, reliable, and integrity, and polite.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:28.46,0:26:33.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Everybody was cordial.\NEverybody did their homework.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:33.14,0:26:38.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Fairness was okay.\NSo we take these for granted.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:38.14,0:26:47.20,Default,,0,0,0,,You think everybody in the world is considerate, responsible, moral, warm, kind, easygoing, tolerant.\NYou try to control your temper.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:47.20,0:26:50.20,Default,,0,0,0,,You just don't ramble off all over the place.\NYou're friendly.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:50.20,0:26:53.20,Default,,0,0,0,,You meet somebody, you say, how do you do?\NPeople are orderly.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:53.20,0:26:57.20,Default,,0,0,0,,They don't either slobby mess every place they go.\NPick up after yourself, young men.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:57.20,0:27:00.36,Default,,0,0,0,,We take these for granted.\NWhole segments of society do not.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:00.36,0:27:11.45,Default,,0,0,0,,They do not pick up after themself.\NOne glimpse of a sidewalk anywhere in any big city, I can tell you what the caliber, level, consciousness of that city is.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:11.45,0:27:19.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Just one glance.\NEverybody I grew up with was sane, fair, ethical.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:19.24,0:27:22.24,Default,,0,0,0,,People tried to stay healthy.\NThey were faithful.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:22.24,0:27:25.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Everybody had a sense of humor.\NThey were rational.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:25.24,0:27:29.24,Default,,0,0,0,,It was reasonable or not reasonable.\NEverybody's intention was benign.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.24,0:27:32.24,Default,,0,0,0,,People were honorable.\NPeople were automatically protective.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:32.24,0:27:37.24,Default,,0,0,0,,If you had a little kid with you, you protected it.\NIf it was somebody else's little kid, everybody was protective of life.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:37.24,0:27:45.72,Default,,0,0,0,,You tried to steer around the cat in the road and not run over it.\NEverybody was humane.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:45.72,0:27:54.17,Default,,0,0,0,,If the animal was sick and aged and in suffering and pain, you tried to put it to sleep.\NYou had to do it, but you did it because you loved the animal, see?
Dialogue: 0,0:27:54.17,0:28:01.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Everybody's interested in being pleasing and happy and glad and positive.\NPeople were generally the salt of the earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:01.17,0:28:07.20,Default,,0,0,0,,They tend to be modest, diplomatic, polite.\NPeople are just sort of automatically nice to each other.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:07.20,0:28:13.20,Default,,0,0,0,,That's the world of the 200s and the 300s.\NThe 200s and the 300s.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:13.20,0:28:20.06,Default,,0,0,0,,It's positive emotion.\NThese are all emotion, but these are not positive.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.06,0:28:30.30,Default,,0,0,0,,From this, you can create a whole different life.\NWhen you think of the large segments of the world's populations that do not express these,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:30.30,0:28:39.37,Default,,0,0,0,,they do not express these attitudes at all.\NOur failure of diplomatic relations with such countries is that we assume they're this way.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:39.37,0:28:53.10,Default,,0,0,0,,They are not.\NThey think being honest is stupid, honorable is dumb, completely the opposite of what we believe.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:53.10,0:29:01.52,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll get to that later.\NThese are the virtues and their effect on brain physiology is what we have to get to.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:01.52,0:29:07.81,Default,,0,0,0,,We're going to move into that.\NThis is about the mind.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:07.81,0:29:14.74,Default,,0,0,0,,We said the mind is silent.\NThis mind, this thing is magnetic.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:14.74,0:29:34.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Isn't that something?\NPeople say I try to meditate, I try to contemplate, but my mind is busy.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:34.48,0:29:40.58,Default,,0,0,0,,No, your mind is not busy.\NYour mind, this is where your mind is, is silent.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:40.58,0:29:47.47,Default,,0,0,0,,This is 1% of your mind.\NThat which you think is your mind is 1%.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:47.47,0:29:53.02,Default,,0,0,0,,1%.\NI try to meditate, but my mind just won't stop.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:53.02,0:29:58.59,Default,,0,0,0,,What won't stop is 1% of your mind is speaking.\NHow do you know it's speaking?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:58.59,0:30:08.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Because of the silence of the 99%.\NYou realize if it wasn't for the silence of the woods, you couldn't hear the birds song, could you?
Dialogue: 0,0:30:08.14,0:30:15.71,Default,,0,0,0,,It's because of the fact that your mind is blank.\NIt's blank.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:15.71,0:30:19.74,Default,,0,0,0,,That's why you can see the A.\NThe only reason you can see this A
Dialogue: 0,0:30:19.74,0:30:26.02,Default,,0,0,0,,is because of the whiteness of the blackboard.\NIsn't that so?
Dialogue: 0,0:30:26.02,0:30:32.50,Default,,0,0,0,,If this was all jammed up with stuff, you couldn't read A.\NAlright, so you're already quite well advanced.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:32.50,0:30:41.82,Default,,0,0,0,,99% of your mind is already silent.\NAnd the 1% is speaking.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:41.82,0:30:50.20,Default,,0,0,0,,If it wasn't for the 99% being silent, you wouldn't know what the 1% was saying.\NAnd the difficulty is not that you have a busy mind,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:50.20,0:30:57.84,Default,,0,0,0,,but you are hypnotized by the 1%.\NHaving heard that, you're already somewhat liberated from its dominance.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:59.03,0:31:06.34,Default,,0,0,0,,You think this is a huge mind full of all kinds of stuff.\NHow would you ever clear it out in a hundred lifetimes?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:06.34,0:31:12.56,Default,,0,0,0,,You don't have to.\NThe mind is 99% silent.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:12.56,0:31:25.15,Default,,0,0,0,,1% is speaking or imaging.\NAnd what you've done is fallen into a hypnotic trance at the 1%.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:25.15,0:31:35.47,Default,,0,0,0,,You are hypnotized and in a trance by the 1%.\NIf it's a silent population, one person talks,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:35.47,0:31:40.47,Default,,0,0,0,,you're going to be dominated by that one person who talks.\NCorrect?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:40.47,0:31:47.95,Default,,0,0,0,,You're not going to listen to the fact that 999 of the people in this population are silent.\NThere's only one idiot chair-ringing away.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:47.95,0:31:56.46,Default,,0,0,0,,No, you're going to say, he is the genius and they're the dumb ones.\NI will listen to him.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:56.46,0:32:00.46,Default,,0,0,0,,He knows how to talk.\NHe's linear.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:00.46,0:32:09.10,Default,,0,0,0,,You folks are non-linear.\NI will listen to the linear and ignore the non-linear.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:09.10,0:32:18.26,Default,,0,0,0,,I will pay attention to the one frog in the ocean and ignore the entire ocean.\NNow I think the whole ocean is full of frogs.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:18.26,0:32:22.26,Default,,0,0,0,,It's just this little frog here, folks.\NThis little frog.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:22.26,0:32:28.38,Default,,0,0,0,,The ocean is not full of frogs.\NIt's full of not-frogs.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:29.41,0:32:35.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Now how does this 1% keep you in its grip?\NIn its thrall, you know, in its thralldom?
Dialogue: 0,0:32:35.41,0:32:41.57,Default,,0,0,0,,How does it gain its power and dominance over you?\NIt's because it politicizes everything.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:41.57,0:32:50.57,Default,,0,0,0,,What would we watch at 5 o'clock or 6 o'clock on TV?\NIt politicizes, moralizes, idealizes, hypothesizes, romanticizes.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:50.57,0:33:00.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Wouldn't that be wonderful?\NCriticizes, emotionalizes, dramatizes, fantasizes, prizes, theorizes.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:00.08,0:33:06.08,Default,,0,0,0,,What happens is the silence gets eyes to death.\NIt's always izing something.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:06.08,0:33:10.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Hypnotizing, victimizing, theorizing.\NPerfecture to victimizing.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:10.08,0:33:15.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's move on to the next.\NUh-huh.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:15.36,0:33:25.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, this is held within consciousness and then it seems to be experiential.\NIt thinks the cause is here.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:25.36,0:33:35.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Actually, the concept is being held in consciousness and demonstrates out in the world.\NThe mind is then the effect, the final result.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:35.26,0:33:41.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Then the mind itself tends to have lower mind and higher mind.\NBelow 200 people mentate.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:41.26,0:33:44.51,Default,,0,0,0,,They mentate.\NThey don't think.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:44.51,0:33:46.70,Default,,0,0,0,,They mentate.\NBut they think they think.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:46.70,0:33:55.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And so there's a calibrated lower mind in esoteric psychology.\NIt calibrates at about 155.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:55.70,0:34:00.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And it's the one that the politician aims for.\NThis is the one...
Dialogue: 0,0:34:01.70,0:34:15.57,Default,,0,0,0,,The politician politician is trying to stir up your feelings and avoid reason, logic, and proof.\NIt can just accuse something of something and stir up the people.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:15.57,0:34:23.70,Default,,0,0,0,,It tries to avoid higher mind, which values truth, logic, and proof.\NYou see?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:23.70,0:34:30.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Say if somebody's a crook, you've got to have evidence that he's a crook and that he stole it, etc.\NSo this side is higher.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:30.70,0:34:33.70,Default,,0,0,0,,It's more...\NIt's more diffuse.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:33.70,0:34:39.73,Default,,0,0,0,,It's appreciative of the beauties of life.\NIt has power rather than...
Dialogue: 0,0:34:39.73,0:34:45.79,Default,,0,0,0,,He relies on the power of truth rather than force.\NIt's more open.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:45.79,0:34:55.79,Default,,0,0,0,,And we say that those people are more evolved.\NThat's the purpose of education is to move people out of just emotionalizing about everything.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:55.79,0:35:01.34,Default,,0,0,0,,You don't have to be a human to emotionalize about everything.\NJust emotionalizing.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:01.34,0:35:08.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Just thinking about them, reflecting on them, beginning to get what the inference and the meaning is.\NOkay.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:08.34,0:35:14.74,Default,,0,0,0,,So we move on.\NThe Power of Intention.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:14.74,0:35:19.54,Default,,0,0,0,,What's the name's new book called, The Power of Intention?\NWayne Dyer.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:19.54,0:35:21.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Wayne Dyer.\NYeah.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:21.54,0:35:30.54,Default,,0,0,0,,As I say, I read the last chapter because you could get it free off the internet.\NThe Power of Intention.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:30.54,0:35:35.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.\NWell, we said that this is how things come about.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:35.02,0:35:53.02,Default,,0,0,0,,As a consequence of intention, the field manifests as a consequence of intention of the infinite potentiality becoming an actuality.\NSo the need for a pointer actualizes a pointer.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:53.02,0:35:56.02,Default,,0,0,0,,It was the need.\NThe need of the pointer.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:56.02,0:36:05.02,Default,,0,0,0,,And then the person who had the pointer also had an intentionality to be useful of service or whatever.\NSo the intentionalities came together.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:05.02,0:36:10.68,Default,,0,0,0,,And then it manifested as such.\NQuantum mechanics demonstrates.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:10.68,0:36:36.40,Default,,0,0,0,,The reason I put it in because there's a certain kind of a scientific, intellectualized, educated mind that objects to spirituality, you know, that it's not logical, etc.\NSo we show how to go from the most primitive up through the evolution of mankind and consciousness up to thinkingness up through the mind.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:36.40,0:36:40.40,Default,,0,0,0,,And from the Newtonian paradigm.\NYou then have to move into 500.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:40.40,0:36:54.40,Default,,0,0,0,,But to get there, you have to move out of the lock-in of the Newtonian paradigm, dualistic, definable over this causing of that on a one-to-one basis.\NOne-to-one basis.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:54.40,0:37:06.40,Default,,0,0,0,,And the way out, the way you can still be logical and be spiritual is to move into what happened to it.\NUh-oh.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:06.40,0:37:10.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh-oh.\NWhat happened to our last line?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:10.58,0:37:12.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, there it is.\NOkay.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:12.65,0:37:22.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Is to move into nonlinear dynamics and quantum mechanics.\NYou know, the reason that it's important for us is because we talk about the power of intention.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:22.84,0:37:33.84,Default,,0,0,0,,And therefore, we're talking about the Heisenberg principle.\NThe state of the world is definable right at this instant via the Schrodinger equations, which are quite complicated.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:33.84,0:37:37.84,Default,,0,0,0,,No, actually, they're not complicated.\NIf you understand them, they're simple.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:37.84,0:37:43.84,Default,,0,0,0,,But they are both time-dependent and time-independent.\NThat's the state, the potentiality of the universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:43.84,0:37:51.16,Default,,0,0,0,,You see, what a thing could be in the next instant depends on what it is right now.\NSo what is the state of this world right now?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:51.16,0:38:07.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Then by intention, which you hold in consciousness, what happens is you cannot do the same experiment twice because having done it once, you've already changed the conditions.\NAnd the consequence is the Dirac equation.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:07.19,0:38:16.70,Default,,0,0,0,,So the Heisenberg principle then is the introduction of the power of intention.\NMany things can come out of a situation.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:16.70,0:38:39.30,Default,,0,0,0,,But because of your intention and the collective intention of other people, you collapse the potentiality, so-called you collapse the wave function, and the potential now becomes the actual.\NTherefore, the collective intention of wide numbers of people has a determining effect on what actually precipitates in the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:39.30,0:38:59.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Our combined intention is influencing the world.\NThe combined intention of this group here, which is a very powerful group, is within the 15%, which is influencing what is happening within the world and is supporting the evolution of consciousness, which is now over 207.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:59.81,0:39:08.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Potential.\NSo the potential of consciousness to move ahead is moved ahead by spiritually oriented people.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:08.10,0:39:12.22,Default,,0,0,0,,And people who are not.\NDon't call themselves spiritual.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:12.22,0:39:20.42,Default,,0,0,0,,They just call themselves honest, hardworking, and pay their taxes, and take care of their family and kids, etc.\NThey don't call that spiritual.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:20.42,0:39:34.62,Default,,0,0,0,,But those are, as you can see, those are the very basics of spirituality, is responsibility, accountability, commitment to others.\NAll right, we'll finish with this, certainly.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:34.62,0:39:43.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, once you, because of intention now, the world has changed.\NAnd therefore, you move from.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:44.67,0:39:56.40,Default,,0,0,0,,The world is defined, calculable by the Schrodinger equations to the Dirac equations.\NThe Dirac equations.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:56.40,0:40:03.59,Default,,0,0,0,,So here's a potential.\NNow you, through intention, you change it into an actual.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:03.59,0:40:07.62,Default,,0,0,0,,This comes from the Schrodinger equations.\NThis is now the Dirac equations.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:07.62,0:40:19.45,Default,,0,0,0,,The Dirac equations now define what are the new Schrodinger equations, the new condition of the universe, from which intention will again move it into another potential.\NAnother potentiality.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:19.45,0:40:38.02,Default,,0,0,0,,So here you see, you might say, scientifically stated, spiritual intention, its power, is via the Heisenberg principle.\NAnd the von Neumann process is a way of describing it, process one and process two.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:38.02,0:40:47.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, its significance is that Einstein is at 499.\NWe said Freud was also at 499, and so was Sir Isaac Newton.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:47.14,0:40:51.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Einstein.\NHe was confronted with this back in the 20s.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:51.14,0:40:55.18,Default,,0,0,0,,This Heisenberg process.\NRefused it.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:55.18,0:41:06.18,Default,,0,0,0,,He did not move, jump the paradigm jump at level 500 to the subjective.\NHe said, I prefer to believe that there's an independent objective universe out there, independent of human consciousness.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:06.18,0:41:16.32,Default,,0,0,0,,And so Einstein calibrated at 499.\NDavid Bohm calibrates at 510.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:16.32,0:41:22.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Because Bohm saw the unmanifest.\NInfinite potential becoming manifest.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:22.32,0:41:33.06,Default,,0,0,0,,He talked about the enfolded and unfolded universe.\NPotential, enfolded, becoming outfolded as a consequence of intention.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:33.06,0:41:44.88,Default,,0,0,0,,So Bohm's work calibrates about 400.\NFreud, of course, made the same error when he, Freud, who is a great genius.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:44.88,0:41:48.88,Default,,0,0,0,,All these people at 499 are great geniuses.\NThey're all great geniuses.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:48.88,0:41:55.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Freud discovered the unconscious.\NThe powerful effect of the unconscious and the fact that you don't know what's in the unconscious, etc.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:55.88,0:42:14.20,Default,,0,0,0,,But Newton and Freud, like Einstein, just did not make the paradigm jump.\NSo you see on the calibrated level of consciousness, 500 is where you jump from a supposedly external objective logical world.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:14.20,0:42:19.71,Default,,0,0,0,,And you begin to live in the subjective.\NIf you look at the...
Dialogue: 0,0:42:19.71,0:42:32.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Mechanistic reductionist who says nothing is real unless I can measure it and describe it scientifically.\NIf you look at the mechanistic reductionist, he says that's true.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:32.90,0:42:37.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Why does he say that's true?\NBecause subjectively it's true.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:37.90,0:42:46.90,Default,,0,0,0,,So the mechanistic reductionist lives in the world of subjectivity the same as the rest of us do.\NHe talks about it in class and sounds very learned.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:46.90,0:42:49.90,Default,,0,0,0,,But on the way home...\NI feel like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:49.90,0:42:51.90,Default,,0,0,0,,I feel like that.\NHe's glad to see the wife.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:51.90,0:42:53.90,Default,,0,0,0,,He's not glad to see the wife.\NHe's glad to see the dog.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:53.90,0:42:58.90,Default,,0,0,0,,He lives in the subjective reality the same as everybody else.\NHe's just being pompous in class.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:58.90,0:43:04.22,Default,,0,0,0,,He wants to sound like a professor.\NOh, God.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:04.22,0:43:07.22,Default,,0,0,0,,I had to give my pomposity a little shot there.\NYou know what I'm saying?
Dialogue: 0,0:43:07.22,0:43:12.58,Default,,0,0,0,,I mean, my old professor was saying, how about me?\NOkay, professor.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:12.58,0:43:15.58,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.\NNow we're called upon by reality, 12 o'clock.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:15.58,0:43:19.63,Default,,0,0,0,,What time do we resume?\N1.30.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:19.63,0:43:21.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, boy.\N20 times.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:21.63,0:43:53.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Anyway, in the meantime, Susan has taught our new African gray.\NWhat did you teach, Rockley?
Dialogue: 0,0:43:53.18,0:44:01.71,Default,,0,0,0,,I said, let's do kinesiology.\NI can't get away from it.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:01.71,0:44:09.75,Default,,0,0,0,,The parrot wants me to do it.\NAll right.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:09.75,0:44:19.25,Default,,0,0,0,,That's enough of the Newtonian and the quantum mechanics and all that.\NThe mind thinks dualistically.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:19.25,0:44:23.98,Default,,0,0,0,,It thinks in terms of an either or.\NHow can you be nonlinear?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:23.98,0:44:30.98,Default,,0,0,0,,I mean, how do you think if you're nonlinear?\NIf you can't think dualistically anymore, it's against the rules.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:30.98,0:44:41.50,Default,,0,0,0,,You begin to see that there are no opposites, that the opposite ism is a product of mentation.\NIn the world, there is no opposite ism.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:41.50,0:44:48.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Just as we said, it's important to know because there is no opposite to truth.\NThere's either its presence or its absence.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:48.50,0:44:54.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Electricity is either running down the wire or it is not.\NThere is no alternate thing called offness.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:54.50,0:45:00.56,Default,,0,0,0,,There's no opposite to electricity called offness.\NIt's either present or not present.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:00.56,0:45:07.26,Default,,0,0,0,,We can demonstrate this with goodness.\NAnd see, there's desirability.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:07.26,0:45:13.26,Default,,0,0,0,,And then here, desirability gets less and less.\NOne variable, desirability.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:13.26,0:45:18.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's take light.\NCertainly, people say light and darkness are opposites.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:18.06,0:45:22.74,Default,,0,0,0,,There's light.\NLight is either present or it is not present.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:22.74,0:45:26.77,Default,,0,0,0,,There's lots of light and then it gets dimmer and dimmer and dimmer.\NAnd now it's absent.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:26.77,0:45:30.99,Default,,0,0,0,,So, darkness is the absence of light.\NJust as.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:30.99,0:45:41.81,Default,,0,0,0,,So, that's applicable, as you see, to spiritual understanding.\NThe same goes, people say, well, what about hot and cold?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:41.81,0:45:49.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Heat is either present or not present.\NIt's extremely present, which we call that very hot.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:49.28,0:45:54.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Or it's not present.\NSo, there is no opposite of heat in this coldness.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:54.28,0:46:00.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Because it's not present.\NIt's a goodness called badness.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:00.21,0:46:06.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Value, again, you see, is just desirability.\NIt's either precious.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:06.68,0:46:10.68,Default,,0,0,0,,It's precious if you want it.\NIf you don't want it, it's worthless.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:10.68,0:46:17.29,Default,,0,0,0,,So, it does not exist out there.\NYou project that onto it and you say, oh, how beautiful.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:17.29,0:46:27.09,Default,,0,0,0,,As you transcend all these illusions and the duality of the opposites,\Nthen you begin to see with increasing beauty.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:27.09,0:46:35.09,Default,,0,0,0,,If you live within the field instead of the content of the field,\None day as you're walking along, suddenly you're struck by the incredible beauty
Dialogue: 0,0:46:35.09,0:46:40.09,Default,,0,0,0,,of something you catch out of the corner of your eye.\NIt's incredible perfection.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:40.09,0:46:46.47,Default,,0,0,0,,It's divinity radiates out to you.\NIt's a gift from God.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:46.47,0:46:58.85,Default,,0,0,0,,You then notice that every weed is incredibly beautiful.\NYou look at a weed and its sculpture is absolutely, incredibly beautiful.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:58.85,0:47:08.51,Default,,0,0,0,,And it waves in the wind and expresses its beauty.\NThe beauty of a weed is the same as the beauty of a flower,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:08.51,0:47:15.88,Default,,0,0,0,,just of a different nature.\NWe're talking about the observer, the witness.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:15.88,0:47:25.07,Default,,0,0,0,,We said the observer witness is faster than ten thousandths of a second.\NSo, if you live in the field rather than the content of the field,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:25.07,0:47:35.10,Default,,0,0,0,,what we're talking about becomes obvious because it becomes experiential.\NYou begin to experience that everything is just the outflowing.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:35.10,0:47:44.05,Default,,0,0,0,,This cannot be picked up by the mind.\NThe mind picks up form.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:44.05,0:47:50.30,Default,,0,0,0,,How do you know you have a mind?\NBecause it registers, you recognize it through the watcher-experiencer.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:50.30,0:47:59.30,Default,,0,0,0,,But it is back here that you transcend the limitation of one-tenth thousandths of a second.\NAnd it becomes apparent that everything is just happening of its own.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:59.30,0:48:06.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Everything is happening of its own.\NWell, what is that crazy sound?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:06.30,0:48:08.30,Default,,0,0,0,,It's happening of its own.\NThank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:08.30,0:48:15.42,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll go on to the next exciting slide.\NYes, we said the power of intention.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:15.42,0:48:20.42,Default,,0,0,0,,The power of intention.\NAnd we'll see how important that is when we get to brain physiology,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:20.42,0:48:28.82,Default,,0,0,0,,which will be coming up shortly.\NThe power of intention.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:28.82,0:48:36.92,Default,,0,0,0,,We noticed an interesting thing when we calibrated the level of the Ganges River.\NThe Ganges River is about as disgusting as you can get.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:36.92,0:48:49.01,Default,,0,0,0,,The sewage of one hundred large cities dumped into the Ganges River\Ndead bodies, feces, all the garbage of the world floats down the Ganges.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:49.01,0:48:54.01,Default,,0,0,0,,And the Ganges calibrates over five hundred.\NHow can that be?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:54.01,0:49:05.58,Default,,0,0,0,,The Ganges River calibrates over five hundred.\NBecause it has been sanctified by the collective intention of Hindus for millennia.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:05.58,0:49:11.42,Default,,0,0,0,,The Ganges River calibrates over five hundred.\NSo I just thought these are very interesting.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:11.42,0:49:21.48,Default,,0,0,0,,And to pronounce it OM, not AUM, which is an error in translation,\Nwhich is an error in Satchitananda.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:21.48,0:49:30.02,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't know if it's Satchitananda's error.\NSatchitananda's, I forget what it is, but anyway.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:30.02,0:49:34.02,Default,,0,0,0,,AUM is not correct.\NAUM is not correct.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:34.02,0:49:41.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, Patanjali's, aphorisms of Patanjali, by Satchitananda.\NAnyway.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:41.02,0:49:45.02,Default,,0,0,0,,It's pronounced AUM, and if you calibrate the difference,\Nthere's quite a bit of difference.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:45.02,0:49:51.02,Default,,0,0,0,,The sound AUM calibrates extremely high.\NAUM is a limitation at 210.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:51.02,0:49:57.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Om Namah Shivaya.\NChandi Chani Om Mani Padme Hum.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:57.43,0:50:00.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Gregorian Chants.\NJapa, the Jesus Prayer.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:00.43,0:50:05.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Saying the Rosary.\NAll these things.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:05.65,0:50:09.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Twelve-step groups calibrated 540.\NThe Golden Rule.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:09.84,0:50:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,See how high all these things are.\NNow, the very interesting thing,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:14.00,0:50:20.19,Default,,0,0,0,,you notice a whole bunch of them calibrated 540,\Nand that's because of the power of intention.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:20.19,0:50:26.19,Default,,0,0,0,,To the Western Newtonian mind, scientific mind,\Nit seems like rotating a prayer wheel
Dialogue: 0,0:50:26.19,0:50:32.19,Default,,0,0,0,,would be an idiotic bit of ignorance, huh?\NExcept that the intention, the intention,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:32.19,0:50:39.19,Default,,0,0,0,,the intention of turning the prayer wheel is 540.\NSo whether prayer is wafted up to heaven or not
Dialogue: 0,0:50:39.19,0:50:43.48,Default,,0,0,0,,is all in your head.\NThe intention is what gives it its power.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:43.48,0:50:50.48,Default,,0,0,0,,The wailing wall, bathing in the Ganges,\Nprayer of Saint Francis of Assisi is at 580.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:50.48,0:50:57.18,Default,,0,0,0,,So devotional acts, devotional acts then.\NSo we sanctify things.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:57.18,0:51:06.57,Default,,0,0,0,,When we say grace in prayer, when we go thusly,\Nour devotion to God at 540
Dialogue: 0,0:51:06.57,0:51:11.89,Default,,0,0,0,,is what the power of the intention is.\NPower of the intention.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:11.89,0:51:19.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay, what's the next one?\NWell, this morning it looked a little pessimistic.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:19.87,0:51:27.45,Default,,0,0,0,,It looks like we're really screwed up forever.\NWe've inherited an animal mind,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:27.45,0:51:35.09,Default,,0,0,0,,which is all sinful from the human spiritual viewpoint,\Nand we've got a prefrontal cortex
Dialogue: 0,0:51:35.09,0:51:41.09,Default,,0,0,0,,that can't tell truth from falsehood.\NWhat a pickle.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:43.18,0:51:47.18,Default,,0,0,0,,The human pickle\Ncan't tell truth from falsehood,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:47.18,0:51:54.18,Default,,0,0,0,,but is spiritually responsible for knowing the difference,\Nwhich it can't know by its own design.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:54.18,0:52:01.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, my God.\NWe are screwed up.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:01.14,0:52:05.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay.\NHow do we transcend that apparent disparity,
Dialogue: 0,0:52:05.14,0:52:09.20,Default,,0,0,0,,that duality between the animal mind\Nand spiritual awareness and intelligence?
Dialogue: 0,0:52:09.20,0:52:14.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we said the prefrontal cortex\Nproduces the calibrated fields in the 400s.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:14.20,0:52:22.31,Default,,0,0,0,,The animal produces consciousness up to 200.\NNow, how do we ever become evolved?
Dialogue: 0,0:52:22.31,0:52:31.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, it's because we would be sort of in a pickle forever\Nif we were limited to the Newtonian paradigm
Dialogue: 0,0:52:31.54,0:52:37.54,Default,,0,0,0,,of protoplasm and causality\Nand the science, the dimensions of science.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:37.54,0:52:46.59,Default,,0,0,0,,The way out of this dilemma is non-protoplasmic.\NYou're not stuck just with your physical brain and your neurons.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:46.59,0:52:50.88,Default,,0,0,0,,The neurons, of course, do evolve\Nas you become more,
Dialogue: 0,0:52:50.88,0:52:55.98,Default,,0,0,0,,more conscious and aware.\NThe neuronal configuration tends to be influenced.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:55.98,0:53:02.98,Default,,0,0,0,,The most fortuitous thing, fortunate thing for children\Nis to grow up with classical music.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:02.98,0:53:09.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Classical music, exposure to some religion,\Ndoesn't make much difference which religion,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:09.01,0:53:17.53,Default,,0,0,0,,but some kind of a spiritual integrity,\Nexposure to classical music.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:17.53,0:53:24.49,Default,,0,0,0,,And on top of that, you can add another 1% by playing chess.\NThe chances of criminality,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:24.49,0:53:29.00,Default,,0,0,0,,if you grew up under those conditions,\Nis practically zilch.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:29.00,0:53:37.52,Default,,0,0,0,,The minimal...\NThose things then bring about a neuronal patterning.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:37.52,0:53:43.65,Default,,0,0,0,,The exposure of classical music,\Nthe classics such as the great books of the Western world,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:43.65,0:53:49.65,Default,,0,0,0,,the exposure to beauty then, the reverence for beauty.\NSo religion of whatever sort gives you a reverence for beauty
Dialogue: 0,0:53:49.65,0:53:55.65,Default,,0,0,0,,and a reverence for truth.\NThis reverence then influences the neuronal patterning.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:55.65,0:53:58.90,Default,,0,0,0,,As you know, neurons\Ncontinue to grow.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:58.90,0:54:07.77,Default,,0,0,0,,And as you energize them with certain vibrational frequencies,\Nthey tend to grow into those.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:07.77,0:54:12.77,Default,,0,0,0,,As you know, when you grow up,\Nyou produce 10 times more neurons than you need.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:12.77,0:54:17.77,Default,,0,0,0,,So they weed out.\NThey weed out the ones that are not needed and unused.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:21.88,0:54:27.32,Default,,0,0,0,,What can we do for our children then?\NWhat can we do for our children?
Dialogue: 0,0:54:27.32,0:54:31.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Our research indicates the greatest things you can do for your children\Nis classical music.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:31.32,0:54:37.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Chess, spiritual integrity,\Nand we'll see even Boy Scouts, Girl Scouts, 4-H,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:37.51,0:54:40.51,Default,,0,0,0,,all those things,\Nwhich teach you the difference between right and wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:40.51,0:54:44.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Spiritual integrity.\NNow, what happens, you see,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:44.99,0:54:48.99,Default,,0,0,0,,below level 200,\Nyou're stuck with a strictly animal brain.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:48.99,0:54:56.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Below 200, the animal brain,\Nthe input, what you see, the sensory input,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:56.40,0:55:02.78,Default,,0,0,0,,is fast relayed through a thing called the thalamus.\NIt's fast tracked to the amygdala,
Dialogue: 0,0:55:02.78,0:55:11.78,Default,,0,0,0,,which is somewhere south of Cincinnati.\NYou have an input quickly relayed to the emotional center.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:11.78,0:55:17.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Screw you.\NAnd now your memory of the event
Dialogue: 0,0:55:17.58,0:55:21.58,Default,,0,0,0,,is stored in your hippocampus,\Nwhich is north of Detroit.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:24.90,0:55:30.34,Default,,0,0,0,,So this is the animal.\NIt sees.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:30.34,0:55:35.34,Default,,0,0,0,,You see, it's got to be fast tracked,\Nfast tracked,
Dialogue: 0,0:55:35.34,0:55:40.34,Default,,0,0,0,,because his survival is dependent on it.\NYou've got to quickly identify friend or foe and react.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:40.34,0:55:45.85,Default,,0,0,0,,You don't have time to think about it.\NSo the left brain human being,
Dialogue: 0,0:55:45.85,0:55:49.85,Default,,0,0,0,,below consciousness level 200,\Nreacts primarily emotionally,
Dialogue: 0,0:55:49.85,0:55:53.88,Default,,0,0,0,,and the input of the cortex,\Nyou see that it's slow.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:53.88,0:55:59.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Slow.\NWe say they're a little slow.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:05.80,0:56:10.47,Default,,0,0,0,,And they are slow. So,\Nwhat's slow is,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:10.47,0:56:16.47,Default,,0,0,0,,is the, what we show in the great books of the Western world.\NWhat's slow is the cerebral cortex.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:16.47,0:56:25.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, what about facts, reason, logic, proof, etc.\NAnd this person just wants to react out of emotion, you see.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:25.94,0:56:30.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright, so what happens at consciousness level 200?\NThen you would be at the effect
Dialogue: 0,0:56:30.94,0:56:37.68,Default,,0,0,0,,and the limitation of your animal.\NNow, if I teach you spiritual religion,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:37.68,0:56:42.51,Default,,0,0,0,,what are you going to do with it?\NWhat's an animal going to do with it?
Dialogue: 0,0:56:42.51,0:56:48.31,Default,,0,0,0,,He's going to use it to kill you with.\NFor Jesus,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:48.31,0:56:52.31,Default,,0,0,0,,for God, for Allah.\NThe animal is going to take religion
Dialogue: 0,0:56:52.31,0:57:00.82,Default,,0,0,0,,and use it as a new weapon with which to kill you.\NI've done it, I know, I know, I've done it.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:00.82,0:57:06.02,Default,,0,0,0,,I told you about that a lifetime.\NI killed him for Jesus and he killed me for Allah.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:06.02,0:57:12.36,Default,,0,0,0,,I mean...\NWith the evolution of consciousness,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:12.36,0:57:15.36,Default,,0,0,0,,then,\Nso below 200,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:15.36,0:57:20.74,Default,,0,0,0,,we have a left brain dominance.\NIt deals in a world that is linear.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:20.74,0:57:24.74,Default,,0,0,0,,It constantly releases stress hormones,\Nadrenaline,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:24.74,0:57:28.81,Default,,0,0,0,,depletes your norepinephrine.\NYou end up on Prozac.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:28.81,0:57:33.06,Default,,0,0,0,,It's set for fight or flight.\NIt's the alarm reaction, you see,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:33.06,0:57:39.22,Default,,0,0,0,,and it leads to exhaustion.\NSelye made it very famous, you know,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:39.22,0:57:43.42,Default,,0,0,0,,as did Canon.\NThe suppression of the thymus gland,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:43.42,0:57:47.42,Default,,0,0,0,,the thymus gland regulates the immune system\Nand balances the acupuncture system.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:47.42,0:57:53.42,Default,,0,0,0,,So with this constant stress, then,\Nyou have less immunity
Dialogue: 0,0:57:53.42,0:57:57.42,Default,,0,0,0,,and decreased circulating killer cells.\NKiller cells are the good guys,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:57.42,0:58:00.42,Default,,0,0,0,,despite their name, Killer.\NThey kill the bad guys.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:00.42,0:58:05.18,Default,,0,0,0,,So you have stress of the thymus gland.\NIt disrupts...
Dialogue: 0,0:58:05.18,0:58:09.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Every time you go below that,\Nyou disrupt the acupuncture system.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:09.18,0:58:13.18,Default,,0,0,0,,As you see with kinesiology,\Nthe arm goes weak.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:13.18,0:58:15.18,Default,,0,0,0,,In the presence of falsehood,\Nthe arm goes weak.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:15.18,0:58:19.18,Default,,0,0,0,,It quickly recovers,\Nbut it repeatedly does that.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:19.18,0:58:26.05,Default,,0,0,0,,As it repeatedly does that,\Nit keeps interrupting the same acupuncture points,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:26.05,0:58:35.43,Default,,0,0,0,,the same transmission of physiologic energy.\NIt gives you a negative kinesiologic response.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:35.43,0:58:41.43,Default,,0,0,0,,It decreases the neurotransmitters,\Nsuch as norepinephrine and serotonin in the brain.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:41.43,0:58:48.29,Default,,0,0,0,,And the track to the emotion is twice as fast\Nas through the mind.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:48.29,0:58:51.29,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.\NAbove consciousness level 200.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:51.29,0:58:56.29,Default,,0,0,0,,It's not difficult to get above 200.\NYou can get above 200 in one second.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:56.29,0:59:02.41,Default,,0,0,0,,In one second, you make a decision.\NAnd suddenly, you're above 200.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:02.41,0:59:07.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Above 200, then, is intention.\NNow, the input is fast.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:07.76,0:59:12.59,Default,,0,0,0,,It's fast.\NThrough the cerebral cortex,
Dialogue: 0,0:59:12.59,0:59:16.75,Default,,0,0,0,,through the etheric brain,\Nvery fast.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:16.75,0:59:21.75,Default,,0,0,0,,So what happens at consciousness level 200\Nis you develop for the first time in evolution
Dialogue: 0,0:59:21.75,0:59:27.04,Default,,0,0,0,,an etheric brain.\NThe etheric brain is energy only,
Dialogue: 0,0:59:27.04,0:59:30.36,Default,,0,0,0,,not protoplasmic.\NWhy?
Dialogue: 0,0:59:30.36,0:59:35.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Because you're dealing with frequencies and energies\Nvery high frequency.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:35.78,0:59:41.78,Default,,0,0,0,,The old vacuum tube will only serve you up to a certain point.\NBeyond that, you need a silicone chip.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:41.78,0:59:47.78,Default,,0,0,0,,You can't handle that many frequencies\Nand that high energy with a vacuum tube.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:47.78,0:59:52.87,Default,,0,0,0,,So now you're dealing over 200.\NYou see, it's a logarithmic.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:52.87,0:59:58.87,Default,,0,0,0,,So above 200, you're dealing with extremely high frequencies.\NAnd now you need a non-protoplasmic.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:58.87,1:00:05.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Protoplasm cannot respond at that frequency.\NYou need something non-protoplasmic,
Dialogue: 0,1:00:05.35,1:00:11.54,Default,,0,0,0,,which is composed of pure energy.\NYou now develop an etheric brain,
Dialogue: 0,1:00:11.54,1:00:17.54,Default,,0,0,0,,which is a purely energy body,\Nnot subject to life or death of the physical body.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:17.54,1:00:21.67,Default,,0,0,0,,So the etheric brain,\Nwhen you go out of your physical body,
Dialogue: 0,1:00:21.67,1:00:25.67,Default,,0,0,0,,you don't come to an end.\NSo what is it that survives?
Dialogue: 0,1:00:25.67,1:00:31.67,Default,,0,0,0,,What is it that carries the karma?\NSo you develop the etheric brain.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:31.67,1:00:36.67,Default,,0,0,0,,The etheric brain now transforms you\Nfrom just an animal
Dialogue: 0,1:00:36.67,1:00:44.50,Default,,0,0,0,,to a spiritually aware, evolved being.\NAbove level 200, you have right brain dominance.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:44.50,1:00:50.01,Default,,0,0,0,,You're dealing in the non-linear.\NInstead of releasing a drug,
Dialogue: 0,1:00:50.01,1:00:54.01,Default,,0,0,0,,you're releasing adrenaline all the time.\NYou're releasing endorphins.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:54.01,1:00:58.20,Default,,0,0,0,,You feel good and happy.\NPositive emotions.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:58.20,1:01:03.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And that supports the thymus gland,\Nwhich is right behind the breastbone.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:03.62,1:01:08.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Because of that, your immunity is high.\NCirculating killer cells,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:08.62,1:01:12.81,Default,,0,0,0,,you can count them, are increased.\NIncreased healing.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:12.81,1:01:18.38,Default,,0,0,0,,You balance the acupuncture system\Nand the kinesiologic response is strong.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:18.38,1:01:22.48,Default,,0,0,0,,So in the presence of truth then,\Nyou have the etheric brain.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:22.48,1:01:28.48,Default,,0,0,0,,And of course, this is very rapid.\NSo now, this was fast to give you an emotion,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:28.48,1:01:34.48,Default,,0,0,0,,such as fear or hatred or anger or greed or something.\NBut now, what's very fast
Dialogue: 0,1:01:34.48,1:01:41.34,Default,,0,0,0,,is through the etheric brain to the amygdala.\NThe emotion now is a consequence
Dialogue: 0,1:01:41.34,1:01:46.41,Default,,0,0,0,,of seeing things spiritually.\NAnd your memory in the hippocampus
Dialogue: 0,1:01:46.41,1:01:51.47,Default,,0,0,0,,is a different memory.\NSo below 200, you experience
Dialogue: 0,1:01:51.47,1:01:56.57,Default,,0,0,0,,a certain thing in a certain way.\NAnd above 200, people experience it a different way.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:56.57,1:02:01.57,Default,,0,0,0,,And they both remember it differently.\NYou know how people's memory of certain events
Dialogue: 0,1:02:01.57,1:02:06.57,Default,,0,0,0,,can be so different.\NYou say, we both saw the same thing, right?
Dialogue: 0,1:02:08.82,1:02:14.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah.\NOkay, so that explains then
Dialogue: 0,1:02:14.10,1:02:19.10,Default,,0,0,0,,the difference in people's opinion of many things\Nbecause they interpret it differently.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:19.10,1:02:23.10,Default,,0,0,0,,And they interpret it differently\Nbecause their brain often
Dialogue: 0,1:02:23.10,1:02:29.10,Default,,0,0,0,,operates differently, that's why.\NThe spiritualized person sees things more benign,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:29.10,1:02:39.92,Default,,0,0,0,,sees the world in a more benign way.\NAgain, we're trying to get out of the box of causality.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:39.92,1:02:45.21,Default,,0,0,0,,There is no this causing a that.\NBecause as long as you believe that,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:45.21,1:02:49.21,Default,,0,0,0,,you're always going to demonize\Nthe this that's causing the that.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:49.21,1:02:54.24,Default,,0,0,0,,There's always the evil perpetrator\Nand then the innocent victim
Dialogue: 0,1:02:54.24,1:02:57.24,Default,,0,0,0,,who now is in competition,\Nin the world of victimhood,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:57.24,1:03:07.10,Default,,0,0,0,,where competition is stiff.\NYeah, victims.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:07.10,1:03:12.10,Default,,0,0,0,,All right, so then how do things come about?\NWell, here we have a correlation now.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:12.10,1:03:16.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Societal problems.\NWe were talking about, this morning,
Dialogue: 0,1:03:16.32,1:03:21.32,Default,,0,0,0,,about the problematic hermeneutics\Nof relativistic epistemology.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:23.80,1:03:30.09,Default,,0,0,0,,And now we'll demonstrate it.\NThere isn't a wicked society
Dialogue: 0,1:03:30.09,1:03:37.60,Default,,0,0,0,,causing the victims within it.\NConsciousness is stratified, see?
Dialogue: 0,1:03:37.60,1:03:42.89,Default,,0,0,0,,It's stratified wherever it goes.\NThere are people that think
Dialogue: 0,1:03:42.89,1:03:48.89,Default,,0,0,0,,the Taj Mahal is ugly\Nand the bathrooms don't work well.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:48.89,1:03:52.89,Default,,0,0,0,,That's how they experience it.\NIt's drafty and the bathrooms don't work well.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:52.89,1:03:57.72,Default,,0,0,0,,And I wouldn't live there if you paid me.\NWell, I wouldn't live there either.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:57.72,1:04:06.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Too many visitors.\NAll right.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:06.10,1:04:10.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Things are the consequence of the field.\NIf they're the consequence of the field,
Dialogue: 0,1:04:10.10,1:04:13.10,Default,,0,0,0,,then we should see a correlation\Nbetween the field
Dialogue: 0,1:04:13.10,1:04:17.84,Default,,0,0,0,,and what is witnessed in society.\NConsciousness level is 600 and over.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:17.84,1:04:20.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Rate of unemployment, zero.\NPoverty, zero.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:20.84,1:04:24.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Happiness, 100%.\NCriminality, zero.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:28.89,1:04:32.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Between consciousness level 500\Nand 600.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:32.89,1:04:34.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Unemployment, zero.\NPoverty, zero.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:34.89,1:04:38.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Happiness, 98%.\NThey just broke their ankle or what,
Dialogue: 0,1:04:38.89,1:04:45.71,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't know.\NCriminality, 0.5%.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:45.71,1:04:51.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Those are fallen gurus, probably.\NSell tickets to heaven or something.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:51.71,1:04:55.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Sell salvation.\NAll right.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:55.78,1:04:59.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Between 400 and 500.\NThis is the world, the Newtonian paradigm
Dialogue: 0,1:04:59.78,1:05:03.78,Default,,0,0,0,,of intellect, the great works of the worst,\Nthe rest of the world.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:03.78,1:05:09.90,Default,,0,0,0,,People of that level, unemployment, 2%.\NPoverty, 0.5%.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:09.90,1:05:15.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Happiness, 70%.\NThey haven't attended these lectures.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:17.54,1:05:22.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Criminality, 2%.\NAll right.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:22.02,1:05:29.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Consciousness level, 300 to 400.\NThat's good intentioned, positive emotions.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:29.59,1:05:33.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Unemployment, 7%.\NThey're probably on unemployment insurance.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:33.59,1:05:41.26,Default,,0,0,0,,When it runs out, that'll drop to zero.\NPoverty, 1%, because they just happen to be lazy.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:41.26,1:05:47.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Happiness is only 50%.\NCriminality, 5%.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:47.13,1:05:51.13,Default,,0,0,0,,People still, usually that's greed.\NGreed.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:51.13,1:05:56.48,Default,,0,0,0,,At this level, it's usually, you know,\NEnron and those kind of people.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:56.48,1:06:00.15,Default,,0,0,0,,WorldCom, all those kind of people.\NAll right.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:00.15,1:06:06.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Now we go 200 to 300.\NUnemployment is still only 8%.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:06.57,1:06:10.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Poverty, 1.5%.\NHappiness seems to be falling down here.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:10.57,1:06:15.14,Default,,0,0,0,,We're down to 40.\NCriminality, 9%.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:15.14,1:06:21.53,Default,,0,0,0,,And now let's see what happens at consciousness level 200.\NAt consciousness level 200,
Dialogue: 0,1:06:21.53,1:06:30.65,Default,,0,0,0,,unemployment goes from 8% to 50%.\NOne drop in consciousness level, low 200,
Dialogue: 0,1:06:30.65,1:06:37.00,Default,,0,0,0,,you go from 8 to 50.\NPoverty goes from 1.5% to 22%.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:37.00,1:06:43.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Happiness drops from 40% to 15%.\NAnd this was the one we had to recheck over.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:43.83,1:06:48.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Criminality is actually 50%.\NPeople take a bribe.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:48.70,1:06:52.70,Default,,0,0,0,,People bribe off people.\NPeople cheat on their income tax.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:52.70,1:06:57.14,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.\NBecause they don't feel guilt yet.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:57.14,1:07:03.39,Default,,0,0,0,,When you drop from 100 to 200,\Nthe unemployment is 50%.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:03.39,1:07:07.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Poverty, 22%.\NHappiness is down to 15%.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:07.39,1:07:13.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Now what happens if you drop below 100?\NAnd a good-sized portion of society
Dialogue: 0,1:07:13.39,1:07:19.46,Default,,0,0,0,,does go from 50 to 100.\NUnemployment is 75%.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:19.46,1:07:24.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Poverty, 40%.\NHappiness, 2%.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:24.51,1:07:29.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Criminality, 91%.\N91%.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:29.86,1:07:36.18,Default,,0,0,0,,When you get to the lower levels, below 50,\Nthe prison populations in the United States
Dialogue: 0,1:07:36.18,1:07:40.18,Default,,0,0,0,,calibrate on an average from 30 to 60, around in there.\NYou're talking about
Dialogue: 0,1:07:40.18,1:07:49.36,Default,,0,0,0,,the criminal population below 50.\NUnemployment is 97%.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:49.36,1:07:56.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Poverty, 65%.\NShould be higher, but they steal a lot of cars.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:03.45,1:08:08.45,Default,,0,0,0,,I used to treat them so I know.\NI treated all these people.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:08.45,1:08:13.06,Default,,0,0,0,,I know what they're up to.\NI used to check to see if I had my fountain pen
Dialogue: 0,1:08:13.06,1:08:17.06,Default,,0,0,0,,when they left the office.\NThey just have sticky fingers.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:17.06,1:08:19.38,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't know.\NThey're living.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:19.38,1:08:23.92,Default,,0,0,0,,But their happiness rate is zero.\NAnd the rate of criminality
Dialogue: 0,1:08:23.92,1:08:27.92,Default,,0,0,0,,is all the way up to 98%.\N98%.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:27.92,1:08:33.92,Default,,0,0,0,,It's a consequence, then, of a level of consciousness.\NIt's not the fault of some segment of society
Dialogue: 0,1:08:33.92,1:08:37.92,Default,,0,0,0,,which is causing people to do these things.\NYou understand?
Dialogue: 0,1:08:37.92,1:08:43.27,Default,,0,0,0,,It's that field.\NSo in that field, this is what surfaces.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:43.27,1:08:47.69,Default,,0,0,0,,And in this field, this is what surfaces.\NYeah?
Dialogue: 0,1:08:47.69,1:08:51.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Mm-hmm.\NWhat brings the figures up, of course,
Dialogue: 0,1:08:51.58,1:08:59.68,Default,,0,0,0,,is education, intention, the things we mentioned,\Nthe emphasis on that which is of beauty,
Dialogue: 0,1:08:59.68,1:09:04.90,Default,,0,0,0,,the beauty of life.\NThere's a lot of graffiti in the New York subway.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:04.90,1:09:11.51,Default,,0,0,0,,There's no graffiti in the Moscow subway\Nand none at all in the great cathedrals of Europe.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:11.51,1:09:14.67,Default,,0,0,0,,See?\NThe power of the beauty is such
Dialogue: 0,1:09:14.67,1:09:20.02,Default,,0,0,0,,you just don't think of graffiti.\NThe Moscow subways are a beautiful, magnificent system.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:20.02,1:09:25.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Each subway station is like a little cathedral.\NYou just don't think of graffiti.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:27.98,1:09:33.72,Default,,0,0,0,,New York subway, graffiti.\NMexico City, graffiti.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:33.72,1:09:39.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Mexico City, sorry, subway calibrates.\NI forget the calibrations are in the book.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:39.72,1:09:46.52,Default,,0,0,0,,The subway in Mexico City calibrates the same as New York City,\Nabout 180 or something.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:46.52,1:09:52.81,Default,,0,0,0,,And so Mexico City got, caught the idea of it.\NNow in the waiting stations and the subway stations,
Dialogue: 0,1:09:52.81,1:09:55.81,Default,,0,0,0,,they put free books.\NWhy?
Dialogue: 0,1:09:55.81,1:09:59.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Because if people are reading,\Nthey're not doing graffiti.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:59.81,1:10:04.81,Default,,0,0,0,,So they've caught on.\NThe way to bring these bottom levels up then
Dialogue: 0,1:10:04.81,1:10:09.81,Default,,0,0,0,,is through education,\Nnot by vilifying some evil doer out there,
Dialogue: 0,1:10:09.81,1:10:14.84,Default,,0,0,0,,capitalism or the government\Nor your parents or somebody.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:14.84,1:10:19.13,Default,,0,0,0,,No.\NOkay, so that's just a very interesting correlation.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:19.13,1:10:29.35,Default,,0,0,0,,So that sort of takes care of causality.\NYeah?
Dialogue: 0,1:10:29.35,1:10:34.48,Default,,0,0,0,,We thought, you know, it's fun, the book I'm doing now.\NIf you can tell there's any truth in falsehood,
Dialogue: 0,1:10:34.48,1:10:40.48,Default,,0,0,0,,what happens if you take that and look at the world?\NLet's say we're coming from a different universe.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:40.48,1:10:46.74,Default,,0,0,0,,The only thing we know how to do is calibrate levels of consciousness.\NWe began to look over the world and see
Dialogue: 0,1:10:46.74,1:10:53.74,Default,,0,0,0,,if we look at levels of truth in various aspects of life,\Nfrom the subway system to books to the literature
Dialogue: 0,1:10:53.74,1:10:58.74,Default,,0,0,0,,to the great battles, et cetera.\NAnd so we did for fun.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:58.74,1:11:03.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Or she did for fun.\NNo, I did it for fun.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:03.21,1:11:10.17,Default,,0,0,0,,She did it, but not for fun.\NI said, honey, we only got 200 movies to go.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:10.17,1:11:16.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Get away from me.\NWe didn't know we were going to end up doing 200,
Dialogue: 0,1:11:16.20,1:11:23.20,Default,,0,0,0,,but we do a bunch of them, and then we think of a bunch more.\NAnd then we got the most famous 100 movies ever produced.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:23.20,1:11:27.20,Default,,0,0,0,,We ended up doing 200 movies, right?\NShow them what happened to you as a result, honey.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:27.20,1:11:42.70,Default,,0,0,0,,No good anymore.\NSo we had to stop at 200.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:42.70,1:11:50.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Anyway, it's interesting.\NSee, all these numerical designations can be confrontive.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:50.70,1:11:57.70,Default,,0,0,0,,If you have a very fixed belief system\Nand you get a calibration that doesn't coincide,
Dialogue: 0,1:11:57.70,1:12:06.08,Default,,0,0,0,,then the thing is to look into it to understand how is it.\NBecause what you're talking about is perception,
Dialogue: 0,1:12:06.08,1:12:11.08,Default,,0,0,0,,and we're just calibrating things\Nas to what is their intrinsic reality.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:11.08,1:12:16.72,Default,,0,0,0,,So move to the next, huh?\NSome of them you would just guess by looking at them.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:16.72,1:12:20.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Some of them are so ghastly, I would never even see them.\NI'll say, what's that about?
Dialogue: 0,1:12:20.72,1:12:24.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Good God, I don't even hear what it's about.\NLet's just go see it.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:24.72,1:12:29.39,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't want to subject myself to that energy field, you know?\NOK.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:29.39,1:12:33.46,Default,,0,0,0,,All right, so what if we calibrate the world?\NHow long have we got today?
Dialogue: 0,1:12:33.46,1:12:37.46,Default,,0,0,0,,I forgot this.\NThere's 40 to this, and we're at 120.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:37.46,1:12:44.61,Default,,0,0,0,,133.\NBreak.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:44.61,1:12:46.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Is that three?\NAnother hour.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:46.61,1:12:49.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, OK.\NAll right.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:49.98,1:12:55.98,Default,,0,0,0,,What happens then if we're from another planet,\Nand we want to know what, before we land on this planet,
Dialogue: 0,1:12:55.98,1:13:01.08,Default,,0,0,0,,what are we going to encounter?\NSo one thing you can do from a different culture
Dialogue: 0,1:13:01.08,1:13:07.21,Default,,0,0,0,,is calibrate the level of consciousness\Nof the people on this planet.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:07.21,1:13:14.24,Default,,0,0,0,,So we see, we said America runs about 421,\Nbut the northern, north, this continent,
Dialogue: 0,1:13:14.24,1:13:17.24,Default,,0,0,0,,this continent,\Nthis whole hemisphere is a very lucky hemisphere.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:17.24,1:13:22.24,Default,,0,0,0,,This is the right side of the world to get born on.\NI'd advise it.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:22.24,1:13:28.65,Default,,0,0,0,,If you come back to this world, pick this hemisphere.\NAmerica's 421.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:28.65,1:13:34.81,Default,,0,0,0,,But generally it runs 415, 410,\Nvarious like that.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:34.81,1:13:40.81,Default,,0,0,0,,South America, Caribbean islands.\NYou see South America's in good shape.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:40.81,1:13:45.81,Default,,0,0,0,,It's close up around 300s,\Nwhich is a very good place to live.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:45.81,1:13:51.81,Default,,0,0,0,,And then right in the middle of this,\Nyou have the anachronism of Haiti at 55.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:51.81,1:13:56.77,Default,,0,0,0,,We were talking this morning about group karma,\Nyou know, group karma.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:56.77,1:14:00.77,Default,,0,0,0,,So these people must have a group karma\Ncoming in at 55.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:00.77,1:14:04.77,Default,,0,0,0,,And of course they celebrate,\Nyou know, they do voodoo and blood sacrifice
Dialogue: 0,1:14:04.77,1:14:10.77,Default,,0,0,0,,and worship demons and things.\NSo that may be a concomitant
Dialogue: 0,1:14:10.77,1:14:15.90,Default,,0,0,0,,of being at level 55.\N55 is not a threat to the world.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:15.90,1:14:21.90,Default,,0,0,0,,55 is too incapacitated by its own internal problems.\NThey're lucky if they have enough to eat.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:21.90,1:14:28.31,Default,,0,0,0,,So I think there's been 20 different attempts\Nto raise the level of consciousness in Haiti,
Dialogue: 0,1:14:28.31,1:14:34.60,Default,,0,0,0,,and none of them has succeeded.\NSo it seems like a karmic propensity, doesn't it?
Dialogue: 0,1:14:34.60,1:14:38.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Right in the middle of a hemisphere like this,\Nyou suddenly have a pocket
Dialogue: 0,1:14:38.60,1:14:42.76,Default,,0,0,0,,that all calibrates at a certain level.\NStrange and peculiar.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:42.76,1:14:47.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's go to the next one.\NThis is just a different way of deepening.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:47.69,1:14:53.85,Default,,0,0,0,,We're depicting this hemisphere.\NYou see Greenland, Canada, Alaska.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:53.85,1:14:58.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Is that Alaska up there?\NWhat is that over there?
Dialogue: 0,1:14:58.26,1:15:03.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Alaska, okay.\NMexico, the Caribbean.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:03.78,1:15:08.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Pretty much the same thing we saw before.\NThis is just delineated Brazil.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:08.78,1:15:13.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Those are good countries.\NThey're in the positive emotions, above 200.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:13.78,1:15:19.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Now we go to the other hemisphere.\NThey say, I would pick the first hemisphere
Dialogue: 0,1:15:19.99,1:15:26.66,Default,,0,0,0,,rather than the second one to get reborn.\NThis hemisphere is Australia at 410.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:26.66,1:15:30.70,Default,,0,0,0,,You see China.\NChina has come up a long way.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:30.70,1:15:36.24,Default,,0,0,0,,China has come up a long way.\NYou see Manchuria.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:36.24,1:15:40.30,Default,,0,0,0,,You see India.\NYou see vast Russia.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:40.30,1:15:44.30,Default,,0,0,0,,And then you look over here.\NHere's India.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:44.30,1:15:49.37,Default,,0,0,0,,And you see Africa and Europe.\NAnd North Africa.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:49.37,1:15:52.40,Default,,0,0,0,,So now you can expect\Nall these.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:52.40,1:15:57.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Here in the middle of Africa,\Nyou got a calibrated level of life at 40.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:57.75,1:16:01.14,Default,,0,0,0,,40, wow.\N40.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:01.14,1:16:11.51,Default,,0,0,0,,What does 40 come forth as?\NRwanda, Civil War, Sudan, starvation, AIDS,
Dialogue: 0,1:16:11.51,1:16:23.66,Default,,0,0,0,,massacres, tribal warfare between chieftains, etc.\NHowever, they're overwhelmed with their own internal problems.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:23.66,1:16:28.76,Default,,0,0,0,,There's no threat to the world.\NThey can barely get by till tomorrow.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:28.76,1:16:32.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Then as you get north,\Nto North Africa,
Dialogue: 0,1:16:32.76,1:16:36.76,Default,,0,0,0,,now you begin to see\Ntheir rising of difficulty.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:36.76,1:16:40.76,Default,,0,0,0,,You see Europe in the 300s to 400s,\NScandinavia,
Dialogue: 0,1:16:40.76,1:16:46.75,Default,,0,0,0,,all doing quite well.\NI don't expect any trouble from Japan either.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:46.75,1:16:50.75,Default,,0,0,0,,So if you're looking for where you're going to find trouble,\Nyou're going to find it here in Africa,
Dialogue: 0,1:16:50.75,1:16:55.75,Default,,0,0,0,,and especially you're going to find it in North Africa.\NIf I don't know anything about the news,
Dialogue: 0,1:16:55.75,1:16:57.75,Default,,0,0,0,,never read it,\NI can look at this map
Dialogue: 0,1:16:57.75,1:17:03.75,Default,,0,0,0,,and tell you where there's going to be a problem.\NBecause 170, 180, 190 now has enough energy to it
Dialogue: 0,1:17:03.75,1:17:09.26,Default,,0,0,0,,that it can do a lot of harm.\NAnd therefore, both sides,
Dialogue: 0,1:17:09.26,1:17:13.71,Default,,0,0,0,,in endless conflicts,\Ntend to calibrate about 190.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:13.71,1:17:17.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Pride, pride, arrogance,\Neye for an eye, etc.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:17.78,1:17:21.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Forgiveness is not in the,\Nforgiveness is not part of
Dialogue: 0,1:17:21.81,1:17:25.81,Default,,0,0,0,,energy fuels 180 or 190.\NSo you can forecast then
Dialogue: 0,1:17:25.81,1:17:31.90,Default,,0,0,0,,the likelihood of what goes on.\NThis would be where
Dialogue: 0,1:17:31.90,1:17:36.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Rwanda and Sudan, etc.\NThis is a more detailed map.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:36.90,1:17:41.18,Default,,0,0,0,,It's so detailed you can't read it.\NSo let's go to the next one.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:41.18,1:17:45.73,Default,,0,0,0,,I thought we took this one out.\NIt escaped.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:45.73,1:17:51.14,Default,,0,0,0,,You saw the distribution of the levels of consciousness.\NIn the prior map we correlated them
Dialogue: 0,1:17:51.14,1:17:56.14,Default,,0,0,0,,with crime, poverty, income, education, etc.\NThis is just the distribution
Dialogue: 0,1:17:56.14,1:18:02.14,Default,,0,0,0,,of AIDS in the world.\NAnd you see the distribution of AIDS
Dialogue: 0,1:18:02.14,1:18:07.72,Default,,0,0,0,,is almost identical to the map we just looked at.\NThe distribution of AIDS then
Dialogue: 0,1:18:07.72,1:18:15.98,Default,,0,0,0,,correlates with level of consciousness.\NNot caused by anything.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:15.98,1:18:22.72,Default,,0,0,0,,The calibration level of 70 to 90\Ngives you no karmic immunity
Dialogue: 0,1:18:22.72,1:18:28.72,Default,,0,0,0,,to a negativity, whatever it might be.\NIf this was closer to the middle ages,
Dialogue: 0,1:18:28.72,1:18:33.88,Default,,0,0,0,,you'd be looking at the distribution\Nof the Black Death and the Plague.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:33.88,1:18:37.88,Default,,0,0,0,,This would be the distribution map\Nof the Black Plague instead of AIDS.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:37.88,1:18:46.70,Default,,0,0,0,,But AIDS is today's Black Plague.\NOkay, so, move on.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:46.70,1:18:52.70,Default,,0,0,0,,It's like the broken window principle.\NThe energy attracts to it
Dialogue: 0,1:18:52.70,1:18:58.59,Default,,0,0,0,,that which is concordant with that energy.\NThat's why it's important to raise
Dialogue: 0,1:18:58.59,1:19:02.94,Default,,0,0,0,,the level of consciousness of people.\NTo pick up the trash on the streets.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:02.94,1:19:06.94,Default,,0,0,0,,You cannot.\NEliminate crime so long as there's trash
Dialogue: 0,1:19:06.94,1:19:12.07,Default,,0,0,0,,on the streets. Not possible.\NBecause they come from the same energy field.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:12.07,1:19:16.23,Default,,0,0,0,,That which doesn't care enough\Nabout its own environment,
Dialogue: 0,1:19:16.23,1:19:20.23,Default,,0,0,0,,that which doesn't care about its fellow human being,\Nthat which doesn't care about
Dialogue: 0,1:19:20.23,1:19:25.58,Default,,0,0,0,,neatness, orderliness, beauty,\Nthen desecrates beauty
Dialogue: 0,1:19:25.58,1:19:29.87,Default,,0,0,0,,and it throws its trash on the street.\NNot my problem.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:29.87,1:19:35.15,Default,,0,0,0,,They get paid to clean it up.\NThe minute you see trash on the streets,
Dialogue: 0,1:19:35.15,1:19:39.95,Default,,0,0,0,,I can tell you what the crime rate is.\NTell you what the crime rate is.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:39.95,1:19:44.59,Default,,0,0,0,,We can go blindfolded.\NAny street, any city in the United States,
Dialogue: 0,1:19:44.59,1:19:49.59,Default,,0,0,0,,any world, look at the street\Nand tell you what the crime rate is there.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:49.59,1:19:54.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay.\NWe're looking at war and peace.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:54.10,1:19:58.42,Default,,0,0,0,,We're looking at history.\NTrying to discern what is the truth
Dialogue: 0,1:19:58.42,1:20:03.42,Default,,0,0,0,,of what value might this be\Nin establishing peace as a reality
Dialogue: 0,1:20:03.42,1:20:08.49,Default,,0,0,0,,other than just a political slogan.\NGenerally, peace is a political slogan.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:08.49,1:20:12.49,Default,,0,0,0,,And people who really want it\Nwouldn't do it for a price.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:12.49,1:20:16.71,Default,,0,0,0,,It's a wonderful political slogan.\NSo most people who talk about peace
Dialogue: 0,1:20:16.71,1:20:21.71,Default,,0,0,0,,are talking about it as a political do-gooderism\Nto win something or other.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:21.71,1:20:27.96,Default,,0,0,0,,They don't really mean it.\NLet's take a war,
Dialogue: 0,1:20:27.96,1:20:32.96,Default,,0,0,0,,well documented in history,\Nabout which there is no currently unfolding mysteries.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:34.96,1:20:39.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, pretty much settled\Nand pretty much
Dialogue: 0,1:20:39.50,1:20:45.73,Default,,0,0,0,,concordance of opinion about this war.\NWhat can we discover about a war
Dialogue: 0,1:20:45.73,1:20:49.73,Default,,0,0,0,,that's applicable to today's world\Nand to the peace in the future?
Dialogue: 0,1:20:49.73,1:20:55.82,Default,,0,0,0,,We see that one of the greatest powers\Nin the World War II
Dialogue: 0,1:20:55.82,1:21:00.82,Default,,0,0,0,,was the heart of Winston Churchill,\Nthe heart of the lion.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:00.82,1:21:05.30,Default,,0,0,0,,It was the heart of the lion at 510\Nthat held together the British people,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:05.30,1:21:10.68,Default,,0,0,0,,held them together, the heart of the lion.\NRoosevelt at 499,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:10.68,1:21:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,later Truman, General Eisenhower, MacArthur.\NThe U.S. government at 395,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:17.00,1:21:22.63,Default,,0,0,0,,in the norm of the invasion.\NHere's Heisenberg,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:22.63,1:21:26.63,Default,,0,0,0,,out of which came the Heisenberg principle.\NWernher von Braun,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:26.63,1:21:30.63,Default,,0,0,0,,the U.S. military.\NAnd here's something we were talking about
Dialogue: 0,1:21:30.63,1:21:34.63,Default,,0,0,0,,at lunch, triage.\NTriage in the essence of,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:34.63,1:21:38.63,Default,,0,0,0,,in the context of the Second World War,\Ncalibrated at 205.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:38.63,1:21:43.02,Default,,0,0,0,,The dropping of the atomic bomb\Nwas triage.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:43.02,1:21:48.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Not understood by.\NThe mind doesn't understand triage
Dialogue: 0,1:21:48.18,1:21:53.53,Default,,0,0,0,,until you get to consciousness level 360.\NIt's understandable in the military.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:53.53,1:21:59.04,Default,,0,0,0,,It's not understandable.\NThe sacrifice of the few for the many.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:59.04,1:22:06.12,Default,,0,0,0,,The...\NHaving to pick the lesser of two evils.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:06.12,1:22:13.12,Default,,0,0,0,,So we look at the dropping of the atomic bomb.\NPresident Truman had to decide
Dialogue: 0,1:22:13.12,1:22:17.50,Default,,0,0,0,,to sacrifice 7 million,\Nthe estimated death rate if we invaded Japan,
Dialogue: 0,1:22:17.50,1:22:21.54,Default,,0,0,0,,was 7 million.\N6 million Japanese and 1 million Americans
Dialogue: 0,1:22:21.54,1:22:27.98,Default,,0,0,0,,against killing 180,000 innocent civilians.\NTriage, then,
Dialogue: 0,1:22:27.98,1:22:35.39,Default,,0,0,0,,is to try to save life.\NPolitically it's demonized as killing life.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:35.39,1:22:42.44,Default,,0,0,0,,You got your choice.\N7 million or 180,000?
Dialogue: 0,1:22:42.44,1:22:46.44,Default,,0,0,0,,So Truman,\Nwe can get what Truman's intention was
Dialogue: 0,1:22:46.44,1:22:51.73,Default,,0,0,0,,and what his level of...\Nintention was at 495.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:51.73,1:22:56.73,Default,,0,0,0,,He was pushing the intellect\Nto do what he thought was best for the world.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:56.73,1:23:01.50,Default,,0,0,0,,You can disagree with him,\Nbut that's what it calibrates at.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:01.50,1:23:04.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Then we have the German military,\Nthe military command.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:04.59,1:23:09.59,Default,,0,0,0,,You see, the military are usually quite integrous.\NIn fact, very often the military
Dialogue: 0,1:23:09.59,1:23:15.59,Default,,0,0,0,,calibrate higher than the generals.\NThe generals were willing to sacrifice...
Dialogue: 0,1:23:15.59,1:23:21.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Hitler was willing to sacrifice the whole German army\Nand, in fact, all the German people, you know.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:21.62,1:23:27.94,Default,,0,0,0,,So U.S. military at Pearl Harbor.\NKamikaze pilots calibrate quite high
Dialogue: 0,1:23:27.94,1:23:34.49,Default,,0,0,0,,and so does the Luftwaffe.\NThen we saw Emperor Hirohito at 200
Dialogue: 0,1:23:34.49,1:23:39.62,Default,,0,0,0,,and Admiral Yamamoto.\NSo you get a chance to look over
Dialogue: 0,1:23:39.62,1:23:44.65,Default,,0,0,0,,what are the facts involved.\NAdolf Hitler at 45.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:44.65,1:23:49.68,Default,,0,0,0,,So if we're going to prevent war in the future,\Nthen we better use consciousness
Dialogue: 0,1:23:49.68,1:23:53.68,Default,,0,0,0,,calibration techniques\Nto diagnose the situation
Dialogue: 0,1:23:53.68,1:23:58.68,Default,,0,0,0,,before we decide on a course of action.\NSo at least you know what you're dealing with.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:58.68,1:24:06.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Adolf Hitler by that time was down to 45.\NStalin was down to 90.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:06.90,1:24:14.44,Default,,0,0,0,,All these dictators are all the way down.\NAnd faithfully and unfortunately for the world,
Dialogue: 0,1:24:14.44,1:24:23.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Nobel Chamberlain calibrated at 185.\NWhen he negotiated a peace treaty with Hitler,
Dialogue: 0,1:24:23.49,1:24:32.61,Default,,0,0,0,,and came home with a news piece on our time,\NHitler thought he was a stupid idiot.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:32.61,1:24:38.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Stupid idiot.\NSucker, how dumb can you get?
Dialogue: 0,1:24:38.38,1:24:43.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Like signing a contract with the mafia.\NI'll pay you back a quarter of a million Tuesday.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:43.38,1:24:46.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Right.\NRight.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:46.38,1:24:48.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Right.\NOkay.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:48.63,1:24:52.63,Default,,0,0,0,,You see the Third Reich.\NNeville Chamberlain said in denial
Dialogue: 0,1:24:52.63,1:25:02.54,Default,,0,0,0,,he was suffering from the\Nimpairment of crippled hermeneutics
Dialogue: 0,1:25:02.54,1:25:13.20,Default,,0,0,0,,of relativistic epistemology.\NDeadly.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:13.20,1:25:16.20,Default,,0,0,0,,It's deadly, folks.\NOkay.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:16.20,1:25:18.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Japanese embassy.\NJapanese government.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:18.20,1:25:24.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Robin Rappenheimer early was an integrist.\NLate he sold out, apparently.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:24.26,1:25:30.36,Default,,0,0,0,,League of Nations didn't do too good at 185.\NPacifists attack up Pearl Harbor.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:30.36,1:25:37.35,Default,,0,0,0,,So you can analyze everything.\NHere's the Cambridge Five.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:37.35,1:25:44.35,Default,,0,0,0,,And this is why we actually ended up with the Iraqi War.\NThe Iraqi War was a fear of atomic power.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:44.35,1:25:46.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Atomic power.\NYeah.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:46.35,1:25:49.35,Default,,0,0,0,,In the hands of the wrong people.\NAnd how did the world,
Dialogue: 0,1:25:49.35,1:25:56.58,Default,,0,0,0,,how did the secret of the atomic bomb get out?\NThe secret of the atomic bomb was sold out
Dialogue: 0,1:25:56.58,1:26:01.79,Default,,0,0,0,,by these people here.\NThese people sold us out.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:01.79,1:26:05.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Americans who turned against their own country\Nwith pseudo-philosophic,
Dialogue: 0,1:26:05.79,1:26:10.79,Default,,0,0,0,,pseudo-spiritual argumentation,\Nwhich is nothing but intellectual egotism.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:10.79,1:26:13.95,Default,,0,0,0,,So we were sold out then.\NAnd because of that,
Dialogue: 0,1:26:13.95,1:26:18.95,Default,,0,0,0,,the world is in current danger.\NAnd now the minute we suspect a rogue nation
Dialogue: 0,1:26:18.95,1:26:24.05,Default,,0,0,0,,has atomic power,\Nall hell breaks loose.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:24.05,1:26:27.34,Default,,0,0,0,,All hell breaks loose.\NNot because of the reality,
Dialogue: 0,1:26:27.34,1:26:32.34,Default,,0,0,0,,but because of the potentiality\Nthat they have access to atomic secrets.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:32.34,1:26:35.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And where did they get them?\NAnd I'm showing you where they came from.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:35.62,1:26:42.68,Default,,0,0,0,,They came from this guy who turned against.\NIt came from the intellectuals
Dialogue: 0,1:26:42.68,1:26:47.71,Default,,0,0,0,,out of the Cambridge Five.\NThat's how it got to Russia.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:47.71,1:26:53.54,Default,,0,0,0,,And Russia was a serious threat.\NWhy?
Dialogue: 0,1:26:53.54,1:26:57.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Because its intention was less than 200,\Nbut its capability was over 200.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:59.61,1:27:04.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Its capability was over 200.\NAnd its intention was below 200.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:04.61,1:27:09.77,Default,,0,0,0,,And that is the danger sign.\NAnd unless society learns that,
Dialogue: 0,1:27:09.77,1:27:16.02,Default,,0,0,0,,war will be with us forever.\NSo what's the practical application?
Dialogue: 0,1:27:16.02,1:27:24.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Is spirituality just airy-fairy?\NSpiritual truth, then,
Dialogue: 0,1:27:24.41,1:27:30.66,Default,,0,0,0,,in daily life,\Nis manifest as integrity.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:30.66,1:27:37.42,Default,,0,0,0,,People don't talk about Jesus and Buddha\Nand holiness and all that in the secular world.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:37.58,1:27:42.58,Default,,0,0,0,,But the beginning of spiritual responsibility\Nis truth and integrity.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:42.58,1:27:47.58,Default,,0,0,0,,So the alignment with truth, then,\Nis not called, labeled spirituality
Dialogue: 0,1:27:47.58,1:27:51.58,Default,,0,0,0,,in the ordinary world.\NBut it is the beginning of real power.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:51.58,1:28:00.10,Default,,0,0,0,,The beginning of real power.\NAnd looking at the history of the world,
Dialogue: 0,1:28:00.10,1:28:04.10,Default,,0,0,0,,in completing this book,\Nseveral years in which we did 7,000 calibrations,
Dialogue: 0,1:28:04.10,1:28:09.93,Default,,0,0,0,,everything in history and current and past life,\None thing became apparent.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:09.93,1:28:16.30,Default,,0,0,0,,The biggest enemy to peace in the world\Nis political naivete
Dialogue: 0,1:28:16.30,1:28:22.03,Default,,0,0,0,,and the clumsiness, awkwardness, and fallacy\Nof international diplomacy.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:22.03,1:28:26.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Absolutely no sense to it,\Nno reason to it, no logic to it,
Dialogue: 0,1:28:26.35,1:28:30.83,Default,,0,0,0,,much less a science to it.\NThere could be no hope of peace
Dialogue: 0,1:28:30.83,1:28:37.15,Default,,0,0,0,,so long as people are dealing with falsehood and illusion.\NSo the dictum of which we speak
Dialogue: 0,1:28:37.15,1:28:41.70,Default,,0,0,0,,is that truth brings peace\Nand falsehood brings war.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:41.70,1:28:46.70,Default,,0,0,0,,You cannot have war without falsehood\Nbecause it's built upon falsehood.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:46.70,1:28:50.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Nor can you have peace without truth.\NSo to establish that, then,
Dialogue: 0,1:28:50.73,1:28:53.73,Default,,0,0,0,,you would have to know what is the difference\Nbetween truth and falsehood.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:53.73,1:28:56.73,Default,,0,0,0,,And inasmuch as the human mind innately\Nis incapable of that,
Dialogue: 0,1:28:56.73,1:29:01.88,Default,,0,0,0,,you can see why the history of mankind\Nhas been what it is.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:01.88,1:29:09.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Only 7% of the time\Nin all of human history
Dialogue: 0,1:29:09.54,1:29:13.58,Default,,0,0,0,,has there been peace.\N7%.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:13.58,1:29:17.58,Default,,0,0,0,,93% of human history\Nhas always been a war.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:17.58,1:29:22.12,Default,,0,0,0,,In my lifetime,\Nthere's already five or six of them.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:22.12,1:29:25.70,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't know how many wars\NI've lost track of them.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:25.70,1:29:29.73,Default,,0,0,0,,World War I had just stopped.\NWe're into World War II.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:29.73,1:29:32.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Then the Korean War, Vietnam War,\Nand go for it.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:32.73,1:29:36.73,Default,,0,0,0,,There's half a dozen wars\Njust in one lifetime, folks.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:36.73,1:29:40.79,Default,,0,0,0,,So peace is something\Nother than a placard
Dialogue: 0,1:29:40.79,1:29:46.89,Default,,0,0,0,,and a protest march.\NPeace is based on radical science.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:46.89,1:29:53.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Radical science of truth.\NSo I put together this
Dialogue: 0,1:29:53.23,1:29:59.95,Default,,0,0,0,,for the sake of internet\Nand international diplomacy.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:59.95,1:30:03.95,Default,,0,0,0,,I've heard interviews on television\Nthat to me were shocking
Dialogue: 0,1:30:03.95,1:30:08.82,Default,,0,0,0,,where an interviewer\Nmockingly suggests
Dialogue: 0,1:30:08.82,1:30:11.82,Default,,0,0,0,,to the president\Nof the largest country in the world,
Dialogue: 0,1:30:11.82,1:30:14.82,Default,,0,0,0,,one of the oldest countries in the world,\N6,000 years of civilization
Dialogue: 0,1:30:14.82,1:30:17.82,Default,,0,0,0,,before America was even thought of,\Nand he's telling him
Dialogue: 0,1:30:17.82,1:30:20.82,Default,,0,0,0,,that he ought to really correct\Nhis internal affairs in his country.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:20.82,1:30:26.82,Default,,0,0,0,,I thought it was so shockingly rude.\NIt was embarrassing.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:26.82,1:30:31.19,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.\NThe president of China is already,
Dialogue: 0,1:30:31.19,1:30:34.19,Default,,0,0,0,,now there's a different one,\Nbut the president of China at that time
Dialogue: 0,1:30:34.19,1:30:38.70,Default,,0,0,0,,calibrated around 455.\NAll right.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:38.70,1:30:42.70,Default,,0,0,0,,So we put together then\Nsome kind of a science
Dialogue: 0,1:30:42.70,1:30:46.73,Default,,0,0,0,,of international diplomacy.\NThere's never been such a thing,
Dialogue: 0,1:30:46.73,1:30:49.05,Default,,0,0,0,,you know,\Nnever been a science
Dialogue: 0,1:30:49.05,1:30:53.05,Default,,0,0,0,,of international diplomacy.\NAnd you can't just do international diplomacy
Dialogue: 0,1:30:53.05,1:30:58.18,Default,,0,0,0,,by votes, tarot cards,\Nyou know,
Dialogue: 0,1:30:58.18,1:31:02.18,Default,,0,0,0,,channeled information.\NAll right.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:02.18,1:31:07.18,Default,,0,0,0,,So this chart is called Us and Them.\NIt's useful in many applications.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:07.18,1:31:09.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Today we're just talking about it\Nbecause it was the implication
Dialogue: 0,1:31:09.18,1:31:13.18,Default,,0,0,0,,for world peace.\NIt's called the Us and Them chart.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:13.18,1:31:16.37,Default,,0,0,0,,It can be your company\Nand other companies.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:16.37,1:31:19.37,Default,,0,0,0,,It can be your company\Nand your target market.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:19.37,1:31:24.37,Default,,0,0,0,,It can be your government association.\NIt can be your part
Dialogue: 0,1:31:24.37,1:31:32.65,Default,,0,0,0,,in civil organizations.\NIt can be the local towns,
Dialogue: 0,1:31:32.65,1:31:36.78,Default,,0,0,0,,it can be your own meeting.\NIt can be any place in our world
Dialogue: 0,1:31:36.78,1:31:40.97,Default,,0,0,0,,where you have two different segments\Nof society dealing with each other.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:40.97,1:31:44.97,Default,,0,0,0,,And this chart is called Us and Them.\NUs and Them.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:44.97,1:31:47.97,Default,,0,0,0,,It gives you some kind of a scientific\Nrational basis upon which
Dialogue: 0,1:31:47.97,1:31:52.00,Default,,0,0,0,,to approach other people.\NFirst you have to know who you are,
Dialogue: 0,1:31:52.00,1:31:57.25,Default,,0,0,0,,then you have to know who them is.\NNobody in this world knows who they are,
Dialogue: 0,1:31:57.25,1:32:01.63,Default,,0,0,0,,much less who them is.\NHow can you have success?
Dialogue: 0,1:32:01.63,1:32:06.11,Default,,0,0,0,,You don't know who you are,\Nand you don't know who they are.
Dialogue: 0,1:32:06.11,1:32:10.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Good God.\NAfter many years of psychoanalysis,
Dialogue: 0,1:32:10.20,1:32:15.45,Default,,0,0,0,,I knew who I was.\NIt was now my job,
Dialogue: 0,1:32:15.45,1:32:18.45,Default,,0,0,0,,when a patient walked in,\Nto get to know who they are.
Dialogue: 0,1:32:18.45,1:32:21.45,Default,,0,0,0,,It wasn't their job\Nto come to where I was.
Dialogue: 0,1:32:21.45,1:32:28.06,Default,,0,0,0,,It was my job to go where they were\Nand build a walkway between us.
Dialogue: 0,1:32:28.06,1:32:31.06,Default,,0,0,0,,All right, so this is Us.\NIn international politics,
Dialogue: 0,1:32:31.06,1:32:35.31,Default,,0,0,0,,which is a profound application\Nof really new science,
Dialogue: 0,1:32:35.31,1:32:39.70,Default,,0,0,0,,this is Us.\NAnd this is Them.
Dialogue: 0,1:32:39.70,1:32:41.70,Default,,0,0,0,,This is the calibrated levels\Nof consciousness
Dialogue: 0,1:32:41.70,1:32:46.18,Default,,0,0,0,,and sort of the predominant\Nemotional field.
Dialogue: 0,1:32:46.18,1:32:49.18,Default,,0,0,0,,You can hear me talking to myself.\NOh my gosh, I can hear myself
Dialogue: 0,1:32:49.18,1:32:51.34,Default,,0,0,0,,talking to myself.\NWow.
Dialogue: 0,1:32:51.34,1:32:53.34,Default,,0,0,0,,My voice goes out the front of my head\Nand comes in the back of my head.
Dialogue: 0,1:32:53.34,1:32:56.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Good God.\NThat was wonderful, sweetheart.
Dialogue: 0,1:32:56.50,1:32:59.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you.\NI can even hear what I'm saying.
Dialogue: 0,1:32:59.33,1:33:03.33,Default,,0,0,0,,All right, so here we have\NAmerica at 421.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:03.33,1:33:14.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Now here's who we're dealing with.\NSort of dumbly,
Dialogue: 0,1:33:14.09,1:33:16.28,Default,,0,0,0,,walk through the world\Ntelling everybody
Dialogue: 0,1:33:16.28,1:33:19.28,Default,,0,0,0,,they ought to be democratic.\NYou should have a democracy.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:19.28,1:33:22.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Why should they have a democracy?\NJust because you think
Dialogue: 0,1:33:22.47,1:33:28.04,Default,,0,0,0,,it's a good idea, huh?\NSo here we are at 421,
Dialogue: 0,1:33:28.04,1:33:31.04,Default,,0,0,0,,and here is where\Nthe other country is.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:31.04,1:33:35.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Now what is their language?\NOur job is to know
Dialogue: 0,1:33:35.42,1:33:38.42,Default,,0,0,0,,what their language is,\Nnot vice versa.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:38.42,1:33:40.42,Default,,0,0,0,,They aren't evolved enough\Nto even be interested
Dialogue: 0,1:33:40.42,1:33:47.96,Default,,0,0,0,,in this chart.\NEven the people of America
Dialogue: 0,1:33:47.96,1:33:54.15,Default,,0,0,0,,are probably not interested in it,\Nbut you're going to get it anyway.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:54.15,1:33:56.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Here we are at 421.\NNow you look at
Dialogue: 0,1:33:56.50,1:33:59.50,Default,,0,0,0,,who you're dealing with.\NYou're pretty safe dealing
Dialogue: 0,1:33:59.50,1:34:04.50,Default,,0,0,0,,with Canadians\Ndespite their politics.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:04.50,1:34:08.50,Default,,0,0,0,,They believe in what they believe,\Nbut they don't know they're stupid.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:08.50,1:34:12.79,Default,,0,0,0,,That's all.\NOkay, so anyway,
Dialogue: 0,1:34:12.79,1:34:14.79,Default,,0,0,0,,now you see\Nwhere is the other country
Dialogue: 0,1:34:14.79,1:34:18.79,Default,,0,0,0,,you're dealing with, huh?\NHere's Central Africa
Dialogue: 0,1:34:18.79,1:34:22.43,Default,,0,0,0,,at 40 to 80.\NYou're lucky to get through
Dialogue: 0,1:34:22.43,1:34:27.43,Default,,0,0,0,,a single day alive.\NIf you're awake at 8 in the morning,
Dialogue: 0,1:34:27.43,1:34:30.62,Default,,0,0,0,,you're lucky to be alive\Nat 4 in the afternoon.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:30.62,1:34:32.62,Default,,0,0,0,,If starvation,\Nlack of water,
Dialogue: 0,1:34:32.62,1:34:34.62,Default,,0,0,0,,deprivation,\Ndisease,
Dialogue: 0,1:34:34.62,1:34:37.62,Default,,0,0,0,,marauding tribal chieftains\Nfrom neighboring tribes
Dialogue: 0,1:34:37.62,1:34:41.72,Default,,0,0,0,,haven't chopped you up yet,\Nyou're lucky to still be breathing.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:41.72,1:34:44.39,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.\NNow,
Dialogue: 0,1:34:44.39,1:34:49.62,Default,,0,0,0,,you look at the Middle East.\NYou see it runs around 180 to 190,
Dialogue: 0,1:34:49.62,1:34:59.30,Default,,0,0,0,,and those are the levels of pride,\Nmilitant pride and getting even.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:59.30,1:35:02.30,Default,,0,0,0,,A tit for a tat,\Nan eye for an eye,
Dialogue: 0,1:35:02.30,1:35:06.30,Default,,0,0,0,,and forgiveness is not something\Nyou can expect of them.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:06.30,1:35:15.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Forgiveness is up around 500.\NYeah.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:15.33,1:35:19.42,Default,,0,0,0,,You look at China in the 300s.\NSouth America.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:19.42,1:35:21.65,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.\NSo what is the context?
Dialogue: 0,1:35:21.65,1:35:24.65,Default,,0,0,0,,What is reality\Nto the people we're talking to?
Dialogue: 0,1:35:24.65,1:35:31.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Reason appeals to Canadians, huh?\NIt appeals to Canadians.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:31.16,1:35:37.31,Default,,0,0,0,,It does not appeal to the Middle East.\NArrogance and pride.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:37.31,1:35:40.89,Default,,0,0,0,,We kill a busload of children,\Nthey kill a busload of children.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:40.89,1:35:42.89,Default,,0,0,0,,We blow up a busload\Nof their diplomats,
Dialogue: 0,1:35:42.89,1:35:45.89,Default,,0,0,0,,they blow up a busload.\NAn eye for an eye
Dialogue: 0,1:35:45.89,1:35:50.14,Default,,0,0,0,,and a tit for a tat.\NSo you know what to expect.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:50.14,1:35:56.14,Default,,0,0,0,,What to expect of who you're dealing with\Nand therefore you know how to appeal to them.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:56.14,1:36:03.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Cultures that are coming from lack\Nwould only be interested in what we offer
Dialogue: 0,1:36:03.51,1:36:09.09,Default,,0,0,0,,if there is a gain to them.\NThey're coming from the solar plexus.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:09.09,1:36:13.47,Default,,0,0,0,,You hear about democracy.\NWhat's in it for me?
Dialogue: 0,1:36:13.47,1:36:19.04,Default,,0,0,0,,What's in it for me?\NYou understand?
Dialogue: 0,1:36:19.04,1:36:23.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Solar plexus is me.\NWhat's in it for me?
Dialogue: 0,1:36:23.42,1:36:26.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Democracy is great.\NWhat's in it for me?
Dialogue: 0,1:36:26.42,1:36:30.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Why should I vote for it?\NBecause it's equality?
Dialogue: 0,1:36:30.42,1:36:35.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Equality.\NCountries like that think that's such a stupid idea.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:35.49,1:36:40.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Stupid idea.\NEquality, giving votes, equality to women,
Dialogue: 0,1:36:40.71,1:36:46.76,Default,,0,0,0,,the lower classes, never mind.\NThey're called dogs.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:46.76,1:36:52.76,Default,,0,0,0,,In their own society,\Ntheir own citizens are called dogs
Dialogue: 0,1:36:52.76,1:36:54.76,Default,,0,0,0,,by their rulers.\NDogs.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:54.76,1:36:58.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Hitler was willing to kill them all\Nbecause they lost the war.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:58.34,1:37:01.34,Default,,0,0,0,,There is dogs.\NSaddam Hussein called them dogs.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:01.34,1:37:09.74,Default,,0,0,0,,These people here see women, children, and dogs.\NDown here.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:09.74,1:37:14.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Should you give these women a vote?\NWhat, dogs?
Dialogue: 0,1:37:14.86,1:37:19.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Women and children and dogs\Nare down at the bottom in such a society.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:19.86,1:37:26.12,Default,,0,0,0,,So you have to know who you're talking to now.\NYou see that these people here are ruled by reason.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:26.12,1:37:30.12,Default,,0,0,0,,These are into willingness.\NThis is all of South America.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:30.12,1:37:35.12,Default,,0,0,0,,You've got very willing people.\NThey're willing to go along with whatever they think is good.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:35.12,1:37:39.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Here you've got neutral.\NHere you've got courage.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:39.12,1:37:44.12,Default,,0,0,0,,But from here on down, you're dealing in pride.\NAnd this is North Africa,
Dialogue: 0,1:37:44.12,1:37:54.08,Default,,0,0,0,,and this is South, Central Africa.\NSo this is true now of any political situation in the world,
Dialogue: 0,1:37:54.08,1:37:57.08,Default,,0,0,0,,economic situation,\Nwhether you're a giant business,
Dialogue: 0,1:37:57.08,1:38:00.08,Default,,0,0,0,,a giant corporation,\Nand you're dealing with a new market.
Dialogue: 0,1:38:01.01,1:38:05.33,Default,,0,0,0,,How do you appeal to that market?\NThat they should buy your product
Dialogue: 0,1:38:05.33,1:38:09.33,Default,,0,0,0,,because your product is so wonderful?\NNo, not wonderful.
Dialogue: 0,1:38:09.33,1:38:13.49,Default,,0,0,0,,How would it appeal to them?\NHow would it appeal to them?
Dialogue: 0,1:38:13.49,1:38:18.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Depends completely on your level of consciousness\Nand their level of consciousness.
Dialogue: 0,1:38:18.74,1:38:24.94,Default,,0,0,0,,And therefore, out of facing the facts,\Nfacing the facts.
Dialogue: 0,1:38:24.94,1:38:28.94,Default,,0,0,0,,See, we fantasize about this country.\NWe fantasize about these cultures.
Dialogue: 0,1:38:28.94,1:38:34.42,Default,,0,0,0,,It's got nothing to do with who they are.\NAll right, so if you want to calibrate a culture,
Dialogue: 0,1:38:34.42,1:38:36.42,Default,,0,0,0,,a country,\Nwhat do you need to know?
Dialogue: 0,1:38:36.42,1:38:40.54,Default,,0,0,0,,You need to know three calibrations.\NWe only showed one today.
Dialogue: 0,1:38:40.54,1:38:46.74,Default,,0,0,0,,You need to know the calibration of the ruler.\NYou have to know that Saddam Hussein calibrates at 75.
Dialogue: 0,1:38:46.74,1:38:56.36,Default,,0,0,0,,At 75, we'll kill you for a buck.\NThen you have to know the calibration of the government.
Dialogue: 0,1:38:56.36,1:39:00.36,Default,,0,0,0,,The government.\NWe know countries where the people are fantastic,
Dialogue: 0,1:39:00.36,1:39:03.36,Default,,0,0,0,,the leaders fantastic,\Nand the government is so rotten,
Dialogue: 0,1:39:03.36,1:39:12.54,Default,,0,0,0,,you take your life in your hands if you drive across the border.\NYou have to know the consciousness level of the people.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:12.54,1:39:18.90,Default,,0,0,0,,The people, the government, and the ruler.\NNow you've got guaranteed success.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:18.90,1:39:26.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Guaranteed.\NWe never ask this.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:26.36,1:39:30.49,Default,,0,0,0,,We have permission to ask this only.\NGuaranteed. Resist.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:30.49,1:39:36.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Wow.\NSame as a scientific experiment.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:36.48,1:39:40.48,Default,,0,0,0,,If you know all the factors involved,\Nyour success rate is extremely high.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:40.48,1:39:46.70,Default,,0,0,0,,So what mankind has been doing over the centuries\Nis trying to maneuver in the dark.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:46.70,1:39:50.70,Default,,0,0,0,,They don't know who they are.\NThey don't know who those people are.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:50.70,1:39:57.25,Default,,0,0,0,,They can't tell the ruler from the people.\NYou get a country that the people are wonderful
Dialogue: 0,1:39:57.25,1:40:02.21,Default,,0,0,0,,and the leaders are crook.\NSo we look at them benignly
Dialogue: 0,1:40:02.21,1:40:08.75,Default,,0,0,0,,because we know the people are lovely.\NI know countries where the ruler
Dialogue: 0,1:40:08.75,1:40:13.75,Default,,0,0,0,,caliber is extremely high.\NIn fact, higher than any other leader in the world.
Dialogue: 0,1:40:13.75,1:40:17.75,Default,,0,0,0,,And the people are adorable.\NAnd we love to visit there.
Dialogue: 0,1:40:17.75,1:40:23.82,Default,,0,0,0,,And the government is rotten through and through.\NLet me just hold that government in mind.
Dialogue: 0,1:40:23.82,1:40:32.88,Default,,0,0,0,,That government, which you'll go on named,\Ncalibrates over 60, 65, 70, 70.
Dialogue: 0,1:40:32.88,1:40:38.90,Default,,0,0,0,,70.\NAre you safe in that country?
Dialogue: 0,1:40:38.90,1:40:41.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Not really.\NLeaders are okay.
Dialogue: 0,1:40:41.09,1:40:44.95,Default,,0,0,0,,People are okay.\NBut if you've got a taillight out,
Dialogue: 0,1:40:44.95,1:40:48.14,Default,,0,0,0,,you may find yourself in jail.\N$10,000 bail.
Dialogue: 0,1:40:48.14,1:40:51.14,Default,,0,0,0,,You ain't got it?\NGet your mother to sell her house.
Dialogue: 0,1:40:51.14,1:40:58.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Now you get bailed out.\NRoutine in that country.
Dialogue: 0,1:40:58.70,1:41:05.68,Default,,0,0,0,,You have countries with very integrous populations\Nand very horrible rulers.
Dialogue: 0,1:41:05.68,1:41:11.10,Default,,0,0,0,,How does that come about?\NThrough the naivete of the people.
Dialogue: 0,1:41:11.10,1:41:15.10,Default,,0,0,0,,You know, Germany was a very,\Nvery good country.
Dialogue: 0,1:41:15.10,1:41:18.10,Default,,0,0,0,,We had a very good country.\NYou know what I'm saying?
Dialogue: 0,1:41:18.10,1:41:20.10,Default,,0,0,0,,So you think,\Nif you're a Catholic,
Dialogue: 0,1:41:20.10,1:41:23.13,Default,,0,0,0,,you're a Protestant,\Nhow can they elect somebody like Hitler
Dialogue: 0,1:41:23.13,1:41:27.13,Default,,0,0,0,,who calibrates to 70 or 80?\NHow can they do that?
Dialogue: 0,1:41:27.13,1:41:29.13,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.\NSo the calibration,
Dialogue: 0,1:41:29.13,1:41:31.13,Default,,0,0,0,,the,\Nthe ruler,
Dialogue: 0,1:41:31.13,1:41:33.19,Default,,0,0,0,,the leader,\Nthe government,
Dialogue: 0,1:41:33.19,1:41:37.58,Default,,0,0,0,,and the people.\NNow your success rate should be close to 100%.
Dialogue: 0,1:41:37.58,1:41:41.58,Default,,0,0,0,,You'd never make a mistake.\NYou shouldn't try to sell people something
Dialogue: 0,1:41:41.58,1:41:44.54,Default,,0,0,0,,that they're not in the market for,\Nand it's meaningless to them.
Dialogue: 0,1:41:44.54,1:41:57.22,Default,,0,0,0,,democracy to these countries here, I'm going to show them how that's going to help them\Nwin. It's going to make them more wealthy, more envied. It has to appeal to their solar
Dialogue: 0,1:41:57.22,1:42:10.79,Default,,0,0,0,,plexus. What do I get out of it? They don't respect integrity because of integrity. A\Nspiritually evolved person respects truth for its own sake. Non-integrist people respect
Dialogue: 0,1:42:10.79,1:42:25.05,Default,,0,0,0,,truth only because what they can get by it. The only use for science is what they can\Nwin with science. They don't respect the Newtonian paradigm for its own intrinsic truth
Dialogue: 0,1:42:25.05,1:42:44.26,Default,,0,0,0,,and beauty. Okay, next thing. Oh, yes, well, this is the Louvre in Paris. The Louvre calibrates\Nat 500, and in the middle of it is this, that was Pi, the architect Pi, modernistic. So
Dialogue: 0,1:42:44.26,1:42:59.31,Default,,0,0,0,,this is a modernistic structure. So here you see\Ntraditional beauty, which the relativistic epistemology disparages, by the way, and would
Dialogue: 0,1:42:59.31,1:43:10.13,Default,,0,0,0,,like to substitute this. Yeah, this belongs somewhere, but not in the middle of the Louvre,\Nin my view of it. Let's see, where are we on that list of slides? I want to see how
Dialogue: 0,1:43:10.13,1:43:31.82,Default,,0,0,0,,fast I have to talk. We did the Louvre, huh? Oh, yeah, okay. Okay, so I don't have to hurry\Naround. I'm going to go to the next slide, and then I'm going to go to the next slide.
Dialogue: 0,1:43:31.82,1:43:42.43,Default,,0,0,0,,How many people have never been to one of these lectures before? Oh, dear, oh, dear.\NWell, I'm glad we did go over the basics then. I thought, because many of the people have
Dialogue: 0,1:43:42.43,1:43:52.59,Default,,0,0,0,,been here before, we might spend more time than usual on questions and answers and explanations,\Npeople like that. And when we do questions and answers and explanations, we leave the
Dialogue: 0,1:43:52.59,1:44:08.35,Default,,0,0,0,,microphone on, so we can share the discussion with the whole audience.\NLet's move to the next one. Oh, this is the new book. As far as it is there, and there's
Dialogue: 0,1:44:08.35,1:44:21.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Gigi. I was saying, oh, my God. Okay. Oh, my God. This is the book a couple of months\Nlater, you know. And where's the book now? Oh, he said, oh, I can't go any further. I
Dialogue: 0,1:44:21.23,1:44:34.64,Default,,0,0,0,,got to rest up. So he took off a couple of months, all right, to go traveling. Let me\Nsee what else we got here now. Let's see. Yeah?
Dialogue: 0,1:44:38.28,1:44:55.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we'll end up with, well, we pretty much covered this subject, 39. We don't need\Nthe slides. So what we've defined now is a way of discerning truth from falsehood for
Dialogue: 0,1:44:55.98,1:45:12.79,Default,,0,0,0,,the first time in human history. We have differentiated between the content of the field, the proximate\Ncontext, that is, the conditions, the time, prevailing elements and influences, and
Dialogue: 0,1:45:13.15,1:45:28.99,Default,,0,0,0,,contrasted that with the absolute. We saw the consciousness calibration gives us, for\Nthe first time, a new tool for survival, for understanding, for spiritual growth and development.
Dialogue: 0,1:45:28.99,1:45:45.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Consequently, we are really a very fortunate generation. Mankind has never had the capacity\Nto tell truth from falsehood. Therefore, he was fated to endless misery, war, all the
Dialogue: 0,1:45:45.97,1:45:47.11,Default,,0,0,0,,catastrophes that we looked at this morning. And we're going to talk about that in a little\Nbit.
Dialogue: 0,1:45:47.85,1:46:08.18,Default,,0,0,0,,All came out of not knowing truth from falsehood. Not knowing truth from falsehood.\NTruth arises then at, or our awareness of truth arises as a consequence of intention.
Dialogue: 0,1:46:08.64,1:46:21.80,Default,,0,0,0,,If our intention is aligned with integrity, we tend to manifest that. We tend to manifest\Nit in our world and in our understanding of the world. To see the world in extremely negative
Dialogue: 0,1:46:21.80,1:46:31.25,Default,,0,0,0,,ways comes out of a lack of integrity.\NYou can't use consciousness calibration to try to prove a positionality. It will constantly
Dialogue: 0,1:46:31.25,1:46:44.95,Default,,0,0,0,,upset you, so I would advise you not to do that. If you're using it to try and prove\Na point. So, it means you cannot have anything riding on a perception. Because perception
Dialogue: 0,1:46:44.95,1:46:54.58,Default,,0,0,0,,and essence are two different things. The difficulty in finishing this sentence is that\Nyou often feel that you've broken into the problem. You have to share it with the community.
Dialogue: 0,1:46:54.58,1:46:54.94,Default,,0,0,0,,And that's what it means. It means you can't solve problems, but at least one problem.\NAnd that's why it's important to understand it.
Dialogue: 0,1:46:54.94,1:46:55.14,Default,,0,0,0,,This is the confusion and uncertainty. This is the feeling that you're having. This is the\Nquestion that I'm having. The obligation of truth to give us. For a trained architect, as well as the
Dialogue: 0,1:46:55.14,1:47:05.58,Default,,0,0,0,,procedure to provide a proper12 hour or one hour of reflection, we can't be more than able to do this.\NThe difficulty in finishing this book is the anticipation of what will be experienced by the reader,
Dialogue: 0,1:47:05.58,1:47:16.58,Default,,0,0,0,,because I'm quite aware of how large groups and various groups in society and the world view certain things.\NAnd this is very often quite some disparity with the essential truth.
Dialogue: 0,1:47:16.58,1:47:25.09,Default,,0,0,0,,The book and the contents are not one and the same thing.\NThe media, of course, exploit that.
Dialogue: 0,1:47:25.09,1:47:36.28,Default,,0,0,0,,So one of the biggest sources of disinformation and lack of integrity is the media, the media.\NIts impact on children, especially, the impact on children.
Dialogue: 0,1:47:36.28,1:47:48.28,Default,,0,0,0,,So it's blamed on the parents, but you'll see that the children are,\Nthe children's consciousness is dominated by the media and by their friends,
Dialogue: 0,1:47:48.28,1:47:54.28,Default,,0,0,0,,the social milieu in which they live, and not by their parents.\NBy the time...
Dialogue: 0,1:47:54.28,1:48:02.91,Default,,0,0,0,,So we...\NWe inculcate this, we try to fortify them against what they're going to experience in the world
Dialogue: 0,1:48:02.91,1:48:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,by the display, by the demonstration of our own integrity,\Nby giving them every advantage that we can,
Dialogue: 0,1:48:12.00,1:48:22.22,Default,,0,0,0,,education, classical music, beauty, ballet, dance,\Nthe appreciation for the great beauty of the world.
Dialogue: 0,1:48:22.22,1:48:32.60,Default,,0,0,0,,You can tell that which calibrates below 100 because it hates and desecrates beauty.\NIt blows up the great Buddha in Afghanistan.
Dialogue: 0,1:48:32.60,1:48:43.40,Default,,0,0,0,,It desecrates the walls of the cathedrals.\NThat which desecrates beauty, then, tells you that is not the way you want to go.
Dialogue: 0,1:48:43.40,1:49:04.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Because beauty is one aspect of the sacred.\NThe attributes of God are truth, love.
Dialogue: 0,1:49:04.43,1:49:18.39,Default,,0,0,0,,The nonlinear dimension, then, is what we merge into with spiritual evolution.\NAs we let go, hanging on to and clutching at opinions and positionalities,
Dialogue: 0,1:49:18.39,1:49:30.78,Default,,0,0,0,,it's more that we open ourselves so that our life then becomes a prayer.\NPeople say, what can I do to advance myself spiritually?
Dialogue: 0,1:49:30.78,1:49:42.51,Default,,0,0,0,,You know, it shocks me that when they ask me at the end of a lecture.\NWell, I suggest you just do this and they own this.
Dialogue: 0,1:49:43.51,1:49:58.20,Default,,0,0,0,,It isn't what you do, it's what you have become.\NSo you become that which is integrous.
Dialogue: 0,1:49:58.20,1:50:03.20,Default,,0,0,0,,You become that which is reliable.\NYou become that which is loving.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:03.20,1:50:15.72,Default,,0,0,0,,You become that which respects beauty.\NIt sanctifies that which is integrous.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:15.72,1:50:24.22,Default,,0,0,0,,By being the field instead of the content of the field, then,\Ninstead of talking about it, instead of preaching it,
Dialogue: 0,1:50:26.22,1:50:31.79,Default,,0,0,0,,you become it.\NIf you become it, you need say anything about it.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:31.79,1:50:48.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Because that which you are radiates its energy to the field.\NYour energy becomes the power of intention which elevates the field.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:48.72,1:50:58.42,Default,,0,0,0,,As the level of the sea rises, it lifts all the ships at sea.\NIt's a sad you would just like to select.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:58.42,1:51:06.37,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll just lift this ship and we'll just lift this ship.\NAnd we'll lift this ship.
Dialogue: 0,1:51:06.37,1:51:14.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Imagine how much energy and power it takes to lift a battleship.\NJust one battleship.
Dialogue: 0,1:51:14.78,1:51:23.52,Default,,0,0,0,,There are thousands on the sea.\NBut if we raise the level of consciousness of mankind only a couple of degrees,
Dialogue: 0,1:51:23.52,1:51:30.90,Default,,0,0,0,,every ship on all the oceans in the world are lifted thereby.\NSo it's our collective intention.
Dialogue: 0,1:51:30.90,1:51:34.90,Default,,0,0,0,,You say, what can I do for God?\NWhat can I do for my fellow human being?
Dialogue: 0,1:51:34.90,1:51:42.86,Default,,0,0,0,,What can I do for peace?\NFor me, you can leave your peace science home.
Dialogue: 0,1:51:42.86,1:51:45.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Why?\NBecause it creates antagonism and conflict.
Dialogue: 0,1:51:45.86,1:51:56.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Dogs, face shields, clubs, bloody bodies.\NThat's a political slogan, politicizing peace.
Dialogue: 0,1:51:56.94,1:52:00.29,Default,,0,0,0,,You become that.\NYou become the field.
Dialogue: 0,1:52:00.29,1:52:07.35,Default,,0,0,0,,You see from our diagram up there.\NYou become the field and by virtue of that which you are,
Dialogue: 0,1:52:07.35,1:52:12.35,Default,,0,0,0,,you are lifting the field.\NThat's what you need to do for the world.
Dialogue: 0,1:52:12.35,1:52:19.70,Default,,0,0,0,,It's that being what the world does not need.\NIt doesn't need another political slogan.
Dialogue: 0,1:52:19.70,1:52:25.70,Default,,0,0,0,,It doesn't need another set of dogs and face shields\Nand clubs and police barricades.
Dialogue: 0,1:52:25.70,1:52:39.05,Default,,0,0,0,,It needs those who uplift society by virtue of that which you have become.\NTherefore, your life becomes, as I've said before,
Dialogue: 0,1:52:39.05,1:52:48.74,Default,,0,0,0,,your life becomes a mudra.\NYou know, in spiritual language, a mudra is a sacred position.
Dialogue: 0,1:52:48.74,1:53:03.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Spiritual work is attacked by many people in sort of a yang kind of a fashion.\NThey're going to go after enlightenment and battle their way to it
Dialogue: 0,1:53:03.12,1:53:12.28,Default,,0,0,0,,through fasts and shaving your head in sandals and walking about in the desert,\Npilgrimages to various places.
Dialogue: 0,1:53:12.28,1:53:18.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Etc.\NThat's the yang way of approaching it.
Dialogue: 0,1:53:18.52,1:53:28.38,Default,,0,0,0,,If you embrace that which is integrous and become it,\Nthen your life becomes like a prayer.
Dialogue: 0,1:53:28.38,1:53:38.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And the spiritual revelation is very yin.\NOne steps back from positionality
Dialogue: 0,1:53:38.43,1:53:46.43,Default,,0,0,0,,and allows the reality to reveal itself,\Nwhich it does unbidden.
Dialogue: 0,1:53:46.43,1:53:52.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Of its own, it reveals itself.\NAs you're walking down the street,
Dialogue: 0,1:53:52.20,1:54:01.42,Default,,0,0,0,,you notice the incredible beauty of the weed.\NAll of a sudden, one day you see its sculpture is absolutely perfect.
Dialogue: 0,1:54:01.42,1:54:10.06,Default,,0,0,0,,One person could create such a sculpture.\NIt would be coming out of the divinity within them
Dialogue: 0,1:54:10.06,1:54:17.06,Default,,0,0,0,,because beauty is the essence of spiritual reality.\NJust as love and forgiveness
Dialogue: 0,1:54:17.06,1:54:27.85,Default,,0,0,0,,and kindness, sharing, tenderness.\NSo when we understand sort of a science of consciousness,
Dialogue: 0,1:54:27.85,1:54:36.85,Default,,0,0,0,,now we can see where everyone is in the world.\NWe can see the innate innocence
Dialogue: 0,1:54:36.85,1:54:44.30,Default,,0,0,0,,of those who are born for whatever karmic propensities\Nto fulfill whatever karmic destinies
Dialogue: 0,1:54:44.30,1:54:48.49,Default,,0,0,0,,via the Rig Veda, let us say,\Nwhich teaches that
Dialogue: 0,1:54:48.49,1:54:59.02,Default,,0,0,0,,that which gives up its life for a higher life\Nearns the karmic right to become that higher life.
Dialogue: 0,1:54:59.02,1:55:09.27,Default,,0,0,0,,When you sacrifice yourself to thee,\Nthen you become entitled to become that.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:09.27,1:55:17.27,Default,,0,0,0,,So what seems to us as needless sacrifice\Nis from a very limited egoistic perception.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:17.27,1:55:28.50,Default,,0,0,0,,What you see are people proceeding\Nto the realization of their own divinity.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:28.50,1:55:36.10,Default,,0,0,0,,What you see is the unfolding of the opportunity\Nto undo the bad karma of that lifetime.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:36.10,1:55:41.10,Default,,0,0,0,,And in the undoing of it,\Nyou see the essence of it
Dialogue: 0,1:55:41.10,1:55:45.10,Default,,0,0,0,,and out of that comes the forgiveness.\NOut of that comes the forgiveness
Dialogue: 0,1:55:45.10,1:55:53.10,Default,,0,0,0,,and out of that one's energy field advances.\NTherefore, it is not necessary to demonize
Dialogue: 0,1:55:53.10,1:55:57.10,Default,,0,0,0,,any aspect of life\Nbecause all of life subserves
Dialogue: 0,1:55:57.10,1:56:02.74,Default,,0,0,0,,the whole, all of life subserves the whole.\NSome of us serve life
Dialogue: 0,1:56:02.74,1:56:12.68,Default,,0,0,0,,by appearing to be sacrificed in the process.\NWe were talking at lunch about the Rig Veda,
Dialogue: 0,1:56:12.68,1:56:20.30,Default,,0,0,0,,which points out that through sacrifice,\Nthrough surrender,
Dialogue: 0,1:56:20.30,1:56:25.37,Default,,0,0,0,,that which is lower life\Nearns its life to become higher life,
Dialogue: 0,1:56:25.37,1:56:30.91,Default,,0,0,0,,which the Native American realized\Nwhen he sacrifices the life of the animal.
Dialogue: 0,1:56:30.91,1:56:34.91,Default,,0,0,0,,The Native American,\Nwhose spirituality he calibrates
Dialogue: 0,1:56:34.91,1:56:40.42,Default,,0,0,0,,extremely high from, by the way,\Nintuited the attractor field
Dialogue: 0,1:56:40.42,1:56:44.42,Default,,0,0,0,,and could even visualize it.\NThe attractor field,
Dialogue: 0,1:56:44.42,1:56:50.42,Default,,0,0,0,,which is the core of a certain animal kingdom.\NSee, each animal kingdom,
Dialogue: 0,1:56:50.42,1:56:56.42,Default,,0,0,0,,the animals all have the same attractor field,\Nthis powerful attractor field then.
Dialogue: 0,1:56:56.42,1:57:04.70,Default,,0,0,0,,So all mules, all horses, all cats, all dogs\Nhave the same
Dialogue: 0,1:57:04.70,1:57:11.80,Default,,0,0,0,,central organizing energy field\Nbecause they don't have individual karma yet.
Dialogue: 0,1:57:11.80,1:57:16.80,Default,,0,0,0,,So the Native American intuited\Nand even saw in their visions
Dialogue: 0,1:57:16.80,1:57:22.80,Default,,0,0,0,,the energy field, the attractor field.\NSo the Natives who worship the,
Dialogue: 0,1:57:22.80,1:57:32.46,Default,,0,0,0,,or pray to the spirit of the tiger,\Nthe spirit of the tiger does rule the forest.
Dialogue: 0,1:57:32.46,1:57:36.46,Default,,0,0,0,,The spirit of the tiger rules the forest.\NIt's a fact.
Dialogue: 0,1:57:36.46,1:57:45.54,Default,,0,0,0,,The tiger is the king of the forest.\NSo when the Native American then
Dialogue: 0,1:57:45.54,1:57:51.54,Default,,0,0,0,,kills in order for a higher life to evolve,\Nwhat it does is it sanctifies
Dialogue: 0,1:57:51.54,1:57:57.82,Default,,0,0,0,,the sacrifice of the animal,\Nwhich by its being sanctified,
Dialogue: 0,1:57:57.82,1:58:04.82,Default,,0,0,0,,it gives up its life for thee, O human,\Nand by virtue of my sacrifice
Dialogue: 0,1:58:04.82,1:58:12.92,Default,,0,0,0,,do I earn becoming one of you.\NThat's the former tiger in me speaking.
